-- ============================================================
-- Batch 24 — 25 affiliate-biased SaaS tools that ship real AI
-- features (Step 41 — scale to 1,500). Drafted via 5 parallel
-- research agents (5 tools each), each verified canonical URL
-- and 2025/2026 pricing tiers via WebFetch.
--
-- AI-relevance: every tool below clears the rule codified
-- 2026-04-27 — each has a named, shipped AI feature in the
-- description / features / our_views (Klaviyo AI, Madgicx AI
-- ad-buying, Customers.ai AI visitor ID, Smartly.io AI
-- creative, Postscript AI / Magic Composer, Xero "Just Ask
-- Xero", QuickBooks Intuit Assist, Expensify SmartScan,
-- FreshBooks AI mileage / OCR, Wave receipt OCR, Deel AI,
-- Rippling AI workflow studio, Lattice AI review drafting,
-- BambooHR AI summaries, Gusto AI Q&A, Sunsama AI scheduling,
-- Akiflow AI triage, Vimcal AI, Read.ai-native, SquadCast
-- (Descript AI editing), Userpilot AI, Pendo Listen / Predict,
-- Userflow AI, FullStory AI, Maze AI Moderator).
--
-- Affiliate metadata stays in RightAIChoice_Affiliate_Master.xlsx,
-- not in the DB. All website_url values are bare canonical
-- domains — no ?ref=, no ?utm_, no affiliate redirector.
-- ============================================================

INSERT INTO tools (
  name, slug, tagline, description, website_url,
  pricing_type, pricing_details, skill_level, has_api, platforms,
  features, integrations, is_published,
  best_for, not_for, editorial_verdict,
  tutorial_urls, limitations, models, community_links, use_cases, our_views,
  last_verified_at
) VALUES
('Klaviyo', 'klaviyo', 'Ecommerce-native email and SMS marketing platform with deep Shopify integration.', 'Klaviyo is a marketing platform built specifically for ecommerce — email, SMS, push, reviews, and a customer data platform layered on top, all keyed off the order, browse, and product events that Shopify, BigCommerce, Magento, and WooCommerce emit natively. Where Mailchimp treats ecom as one of many use cases, Klaviyo treats it as the only use case, and the segmentation, flow, and reporting primitives reflect that.

The core product is a flow and campaign engine — abandoned cart, browse abandonment, post-purchase, win-back, replenishment, VIP — preassembled with templates that work out of the box and exposed as a drag-and-drop canvas you can extend. Predictive analytics (CLV, churn risk, expected next order date) feed the segment builder, so audiences like "high-CLV customers likely to churn in 30 days" are one click away.

Klaviyo went public in 2023 and has continued to push upmarket: the CDP product, AI content generation, multi-account orgs, and a Reviews module are all 2024–2025 additions aimed at consolidating the ecom marketing stack into one vendor. SMS is built in (not a partner integration), which matters for unified profiles, attribution, and quiet-hours / consent compliance.

It is the default pick for Shopify brands once they outgrow Shopify Email or Mailchimp — typically once a brand crosses ~$500k/year and segmentation starts paying back the price gap.', 'https://klaviyo.com', 'freemium', '[{"plan":"Free","price":"$0","features":["Up to 250 active profiles","500 monthly email sends","150 monthly SMS/MMS credits","Email support"]},{"plan":"Email","price":"From $45/month","features":["15,000 emails/month at entry tier","350+ integrations","Customer profiles and segmentation","AI content generation","Reporting dashboards"]},{"plan":"Email + Mobile","price":"From $60/month","features":["15,000 emails plus 1,250 mobile credits","SMS, MMS, WhatsApp","Multi-channel segmentation","All Email-tier features"]},{"plan":"Add-ons","price":"From $25–$500/month","features":["Reviews from $25/mo","Marketing Analytics from $100/mo","Advanced Data Platform (CDP) from $500/mo"]}]'::jsonb, 'beginner', true, '{"web","api"}', '{"Drag-and-drop flow and campaign builder","Pre-built ecommerce flows (abandoned cart, browse, post-purchase, win-back)","Predictive analytics (CLV, churn risk, next order date)","Native SMS, MMS, WhatsApp, push, and email","Segmentation on order, browse, and product events","AI subject-line and copy generation","Reviews module (collect, display, syndicate)","Built-in CDP for unified profiles","A/B testing on subject, content, send time","Benchmarks against your industry peers","Deliverability infrastructure with dedicated IPs at scale"}', '{"Shopify","BigCommerce","Magento","WooCommerce","Salesforce Commerce Cloud","Stripe","Recharge","Yotpo","Gorgias","Zendesk","Meta Ads","Google Ads","Facebook Custom Audiences","Stamped","Okendo","ShipStation"}', true, '{"Shopify and BigCommerce brands above ~$500k/year","DTC ecom teams running multi-channel lifecycle","Brands consolidating email + SMS into one vendor","Marketers who need predictive segmentation"}', '{"B2B SaaS lifecycle (HubSpot or Customer.io fit better)","Pre-revenue stores under $50k/year (Shopify Email is enough)","Content publishers and newsletters (Beehiiv, Substack are simpler)"}', 'The default ecommerce email and SMS platform in 2026. Worth the price once you have enough order data for the predictive features and segmentation to actually pay back.', '{"https://help.klaviyo.com/hc/en-us"}', 'Pricing scales aggressively with active profile count — bills can double on a Black Friday list spike. SMS credits vary wildly by destination country (UK costs 5 credits per SMS vs 1 in the US), so international brands need to model this carefully. Deliverability on shared IPs is fine for most senders but heavy senders should plan for dedicated IPs. CDP and Marketing Analytics add-ons stack on top of the base plan and push total cost past pure-play ESPs quickly.', '{}', '{"reddit_threads":[]}'::jsonb, '{"Run a full lifecycle program (welcome, abandoned cart, post-purchase, win-back) on Shopify.","Build a high-CLV-likely-to-churn segment and trigger a hand-crafted retention flow.","Send an SMS-first campaign for a flash sale with profile-aware quiet-hours.","Pull predicted next-order dates into a replenishment campaign for consumables."}', 'Sweet spot: a Shopify or BigCommerce brand doing $500k–$50M/year that wants email and SMS in one tool, predictive segmentation that uses real order data, and pre-built flows that work the day you turn them on. The integration depth with Shopify is genuinely better than every alternative — events, profiles, and product data sync without glue code.

Failure modes. The pricing curve catches teams off guard: a profile-count spike during a campaign, a poorly-pruned suppression list, or sending to inactive subscribers can balloon the monthly bill. Klaviyo also rewards brands that actively prune — leave dead profiles in your account and you pay for them. Add-on creep is real; many teams end up with Reviews, Marketing Analytics, and CDP all enabled and find the bill has tripled.

What to pilot. Migrate one flow (abandoned cart) and one campaign program from your current ESP. Run for 30 days and compare revenue per recipient and unsubscribe rate against your baseline. If the predictive segments and Shopify event depth produce a ≥15% lift in revenue per send, the price is justified; if not, a cheaper ESP plus disciplined segmentation will get you most of the way.', now()),
('Madgicx', 'madgicx', 'AI ad-buying platform for Meta and Google with automation, targeting, and attribution.', 'Madgicx is a Meta and Google ads optimisation layer aimed at DTC ecommerce. It plugs into your ad accounts and adds three things vanilla Ads Manager does not: ML-driven audience and creative recommendations, rule-based automations that pause/scale ads on your KPIs (ROAS, CPA, frequency), and a unified analytics view that ties Meta + Google + Shopify revenue into one dashboard.

The product is organised around modules: AI Marketer suggests budget shifts and creative tests, the Bid Optimiser auto-adjusts bids, Audience Studio builds and refreshes Meta custom and lookalike audiences, Creative Insights surfaces winning ad variants by hook/CTA/format, and Tracking Pro is a server-side conversion layer that compensates for iOS 14+ signal loss. The 7-day free trial gives full access to most modules.

Madgicx is built for performance marketers and agency operators running ads at $5k–$500k/month who want one console instead of bouncing between Ads Manager, GA4, and a spreadsheet. It is not an agency or a managed service — you still own the strategy; Madgicx automates the execution.', 'https://madgicx.com', 'subscription', '[{"plan":"Madgicx Pro Complete with AI","price":"Dynamic — based on monthly ad spend bracket (under $1K to $30K+) and billing frequency (monthly/quarterly/annual)","features":["AI Marketer recommendations","Bid Optimiser","Audience Studio","Creative Insights","Automation rules","7-day free trial"]},{"plan":"Tracking Pro add-on","price":"$49/month per connected account (quarterly/annual discounts)","features":["Server-to-server Facebook tracking","Enhanced conversions with FBC support","First-party conversion data","Real-time attribution"]}]'::jsonb, 'intermediate', false, '{"web"}', '{"AI Marketer — daily budget and creative recommendations","Rule-based automation (pause/scale on ROAS, CPA, frequency)","Bid Optimiser for Meta campaigns","Audience Studio with 100+ pre-built segments","Creative Insights — winning hook/CTA/format analysis","Unified Meta + Google + Shopify reporting","Server-side tracking via Tracking Pro","One-click campaign duplication and structure templates","Slack/email alerts on KPI breaches"}', '{"Meta Ads","Google Ads","Shopify","Google Analytics 4","Facebook Conversions API","TikTok Ads (limited)"}', true, '{"DTC brands spending $5k–$500k/month on Meta + Google","Performance marketers tired of switching between Ads Manager and GA4","Agencies managing 5–50 ecom accounts","Teams that want automation without writing scripts"}', '{"Brands spending under $2k/month on ads (overkill, manual is fine)","Pure B2B lead-gen (the audience and creative tools are ecom-shaped)","Teams without a clear KPI (automation rules need targets)"}', 'A solid mid-market Meta optimisation layer if you actually run rule-based automation and use the creative analytics. Skip if your spend is too small for the subscription to pay back, or if you already use Triple Whale + Northbeam.', '{"https://madgicx.com/blog","https://help.madgicx.com/"}', 'Pricing is dynamic and only visible inside the app — hard to budget upfront, especially as ad spend scales. Tracking Pro is sold separately at $49/account, so multi-brand agencies stack add-on cost. Meta-first by design — Google features exist but lag Meta; TikTok and LinkedIn are thin. The AI recommendations are useful but not magic; you still need a human reviewing daily. Server-side tracking accuracy depends on your Shopify and pixel setup quality.', '{}', '{"reddit_threads":[]}'::jsonb, '{"Auto-pause ad sets that breach a CPA threshold for 3 consecutive days.","Run a creative test where Madgicx auto-promotes the winning ad based on 7-day ROAS.","Build a lookalike from your top-CLV Shopify customers without exporting CSVs.","Get a single weekly view of Meta + Google + Shopify revenue without GA4 wrangling."}', 'Sweet spot: a DTC brand spending roughly $10k–$200k/month on Meta plus Google that wants automation and creative analytics without paying agency retainer prices. Teams that actually configure the automation rules — not just install and forget — see real time savings, often a half-day per week of operator work eliminated.

Failure modes. Brands install Madgicx, leave the automations in default state, and treat it as a fancier dashboard. That misses the entire value prop. The opaque pricing model also bites: when ad spend scales, the subscription tier moves up automatically, and the Tracking Pro add-on adds per-account cost that can sneak past finance. Teams that already invested in Triple Whale or Northbeam will find significant overlap and should pick one or the other.

What to pilot. Run the 7-day trial against one ad account, configure 3 automation rules tied to your real KPIs, and measure operator hours saved plus any change in account ROAS over 14 days post-trial. If you save 3+ hours per week and ROAS holds or improves, the subscription is paid for. If the automations sit unused after a week, the value is not there for your team.', now()),
('Customers.ai', 'customers-ai', 'Visitor identification and audience pixel that turns anonymous ecom traffic into named contacts.', 'Customers.ai (formerly Mobile Monkey) is a visitor identification and audience-building platform for ecommerce. The X-Ray Pixel sits on your site, identifies a portion of anonymous visitors against a 250M+ identity graph, and pushes resolved profiles (name, email, sometimes phone) into your ESP, CRM, and ad platforms. The pitch: every shopper who browsed but did not log in becomes a contact you can email, retarget, and segment.

Beyond pure identification, the platform layers in audience syncing to Meta Ads and Google Ads (replacing the cookie-based custom audiences that iOS 14+ broke), automated email/SMS sequences for identified visitors, and integrations into Klaviyo, Mailchimp, HubSpot, and Shopify. The end-to-end flow — visitor lands, gets resolved, lands in Klaviyo within seconds, gets a triggered abandoned-browse flow — is the core product loop.

Pricing is resolution-based: you pay per identified visitor, not per pageview. The Starter tier at $600/month covers 3,000 resolutions; brands typically resolve 10–25% of US visitors. Customers.ai sits at the intersection of two regulatory grey zones (third-party identity resolution and post-iOS-14 attribution), so legal/compliance review is non-optional before deploying.', 'https://customers.ai', 'subscription', '[{"plan":"Starter","price":"$600/month","features":["3,000 resolutions/month","$0.20 per additional resolution","X-Ray Pixel","All integrations","1:1 onboarding"]},{"plan":"Grow","price":"$900/month","features":["5,000 resolutions/month","$0.18 per additional resolution","All Starter features"]},{"plan":"Scale","price":"$1,500/month","features":["10,000 resolutions/month","$0.15 per additional resolution","All Grow features"]},{"plan":"Enterprise","price":"Custom","features":["Volume discounts","Dedicated CSM","Custom integrations","SLA"]},{"plan":"Free Trial","price":"$0","features":["7 days","500 resolutions","No credit card required"]}]'::jsonb, 'intermediate', true, '{"web","api"}', '{"X-Ray Pixel for visitor identification","Identity resolution against 250M+ profile graph","Real-time push to Klaviyo, Mailchimp, HubSpot, Shopify","Meta Ads and Google Ads custom audience sync","Automated email/SMS sequences for identified visitors","Audience segmentation on visit behaviour","Resolution rate and revenue attribution dashboards","Bot and known-customer filtering","Onboarding and pixel placement support"}', '{"Klaviyo","Mailchimp","HubSpot","ActiveCampaign","Shopify","Meta Ads","Google Ads","Salesforce","Zapier"}', true, '{"DTC ecom brands with strong organic traffic","Brands wanting to rebuild post-iOS-14 retargeting audiences","Mid-market sites with ≥50k monthly US visitors","Teams with abandoned-browse flows ready to receive the data"}', '{"Sites with mostly non-US traffic (resolution rates collapse)","Privacy-strict regions (GDPR, CCPA-strict) without legal review","Brands without a working ESP or ad-account sync to receive contacts","B2B lead-gen (different product class — RB2B, Clearbit fit better)"}', 'A genuinely useful tool for US ecom brands whose retargeting collapsed after iOS 14, but only after legal sign-off. The economics work above ~$1M/year in DTC revenue; below that the subscription rarely pays back.', '{"https://customers.ai/help"}', 'Resolution rates are highest in the US and degrade fast outside it — international brands often see far lower yields than the marketing implies. Identity resolution sits in a grey area for GDPR and CCPA — you need clear privacy disclosure, opt-in handling, and likely legal review before launch. Email deliverability of newly-resolved contacts is materially worse than opted-in lists; sending too aggressively burns your sender reputation. Pricing is per resolution, so a viral traffic spike inflates the bill. The platform is one of several in this category (Retention.com, Identifi.ai) and switching costs are low — shop the market.', '{}', '{"reddit_threads":[]}'::jsonb, '{"Resolve anonymous browse-abandoners and trigger a Klaviyo flow within minutes.","Rebuild Meta retargeting audiences from first-party identified visitors.","Identify visitors who viewed a high-intent product page but did not add to cart.","Sync resolved profiles into HubSpot for outbound on B2B-adjacent ecom (e.g. wholesale)."}', 'Sweet spot: a US-heavy DTC brand doing $2M–$50M/year that has solid abandoned-browse infrastructure in Klaviyo, watched iOS 14 wreck their Meta retargeting, and has legal comfort with third-party identity resolution. The lift on abandoned-browse revenue is the single most reliable win — a 5–15% recovered-revenue bump is realistic if your downstream flow is good.

Failure modes. Brands install the pixel, send blast emails to resolved contacts, and tank their domain reputation in two weeks. Resolved visitors did not opt in to your list — treat them as a low-trust segment with conservative content and clear unsubscribe paths, or you will burn deliverability across your whole program. The other failure is regional: deploying without checking data-protection law in your visitors'' jurisdictions can produce real regulatory exposure.

What to pilot. Run the 7-day trial. Resolve 500 visitors, send through one carefully written abandoned-browse flow (not a blast), and measure (a) deliverability metrics on your main domain, (b) revenue attributable to resolved contacts, and (c) any rise in spam complaints. If revenue clears the subscription cost without harming deliverability, scale up; if either signal goes wrong, the tool is not for you, regardless of the pitch.', now()),
('Smartly.io', 'smartly-io', 'Enterprise paid social creative automation for Meta, TikTok, Pinterest, and Google.', 'Smartly.io is an enterprise creative-automation platform for paid social. Its core promise: produce, test, and ship thousands of ad variants across Meta, TikTok, Pinterest, Snap, and Google without manual creative ops. Brands feed in product feeds, brand templates, and audience targeting; Smartly fans those into per-SKU, per-audience, per-locale ad variants and pushes them live with structured naming, automated rules, and centralised reporting.

The platform combines four things: a Dynamic Creative module that templatises ads from product feeds, a Campaign Studio for cross-channel campaign structures, automated rules and pacing for budget management, and a unified analytics layer that rolls Meta + TikTok + Pinterest + Google performance into one view. Predictive Budget Allocation and AI creative variation are 2024–2025 layers added on top.

Smartly is sales-led — pricing is custom, typically a percentage of managed ad spend or a flat platform fee starting in the high four figures per month. The customer base is large DTC brands (Sephora, eBay, Disney) and global enterprises with creative-ops teams. It is overkill for SMBs; for enterprises running localised, multi-market, multi-product creative at scale, it is one of two or three serious options (alongside Pencil/Brandtech and Adriel).', 'https://smartly.io', 'paid', '[{"plan":"Enterprise","price":"Custom — sales-led, typically a % of managed ad spend or platform fee","features":["Dynamic creative from product feeds","Cross-channel campaign automation (Meta, TikTok, Pinterest, Snap, Google)","Predictive Budget Allocation","AI creative variation","Centralised reporting and attribution","Brand template and creative governance","Onboarding and dedicated CSM","SLA and support"]}]'::jsonb, 'advanced', true, '{"web","api"}', '{"Dynamic Creative from product feeds","Cross-channel campaign structuring","Automated rules and budget pacing","Predictive Budget Allocation across channels","AI creative variation and copy generation","Brand template enforcement","Localisation across markets and languages","Bulk ad generation and editing","Unified Meta + TikTok + Pinterest + Snap + Google reporting","Creative performance analytics by hook/format/audience","API for programmatic ad builds"}', '{"Meta Ads","TikTok Ads","Pinterest Ads","Snapchat Ads","Google Ads","YouTube","LinkedIn Ads","Shopify","Salesforce Commerce Cloud","Adobe Experience Manager","Google Analytics 4","Looker"}', true, '{"Enterprise DTC brands managing creative across multiple markets","Performance teams running thousands of variants per quarter","Agencies with enterprise ecom rosters","Brands with dedicated creative-ops headcount"}', '{"SMBs spending under $50k/month on paid social","Single-market, single-product brands (overkill)","Teams without internal creative ops to feed the platform"}', 'The serious choice for enterprise creative automation across paid social. Worth the spend if you have the volume and ops to feed it; ignore otherwise — the price floor is well above what mid-market brands need.', '{"https://www.smartly.io/resources","https://support.smartly.io/"}', 'Pricing is opaque and sales-led, with a high entry floor — typically a six-figure annual commitment. The platform is powerful but only if you have brand templates, product feeds, and creative ops disciplined enough to feed it; brands without that operating maturity get less value than the price implies. Onboarding is multi-week. The Google and LinkedIn integrations lag Meta and TikTok in feature depth. Vendor lock-in is real once your campaign structures and templates live inside Smartly.', '{}', '{"reddit_threads":[]}'::jsonb, '{"Generate 5,000 localised product ads across Meta and TikTok from a single template plus product feed.","Run a global brand campaign with per-market creative variation and centralised reporting.","Automate budget reallocation between Meta and TikTok based on rolling 7-day ROAS.","Enforce brand templates so regional teams cannot publish off-brand creative."}', 'Sweet spot: a global enterprise ecom or DTC brand spending $1M+/month on paid social, with a creative-ops team, brand templates, and a real product feed. At that scale, the operator-hour savings and creative throughput pay back the platform fee — sometimes within a quarter. Below that profile, simpler stacks (Madgicx, AdEspresso, native Ads Manager) deliver more value per dollar.

Failure modes. Buying Smartly without the operating model to feed it is the most common mistake — the platform optimises a process that has to already exist. The second is using it as a reporting tool while continuing to publish ads natively; that loses the entire creative-automation upside. The third is enterprise procurement creep: by the time you sign, scope and price often look very different from the demo.

What to pilot. Negotiate a paid pilot or short-term contract on one brand or one market. Build out the template + feed + automation stack end-to-end, run it for 60 days, and measure (a) creative throughput vs prior baseline, (b) operator hours saved, and (c) blended ROAS. If creative throughput at least triples and operator hours drop materially, expand. If the team struggles to feed the platform, the issue is your operating model, not the tool.', now()),
('Postscript', 'postscript', 'SMS marketing platform built for Shopify with deep ecom flows and conversational commerce.', 'Postscript is an SMS marketing platform purpose-built for Shopify. It handles the full lifecycle: opt-in capture (popups, checkout, keywords, dedicated landing pages), list management with consent and quiet hours, campaign sends, automated flows (abandoned cart, browse abandonment, post-purchase, win-back), conversational two-way messaging, and analytics tied to Shopify revenue attribution.

The product differentiates from generic SMS tools (Twilio, Attentive) on two axes. First, Shopify-native data: every event, segment, and flow can reference Shopify orders, products, and customer attributes without ETL. Second, the conversational layer — Postscript Sales is a human-in-the-loop product where AI suggests responses to inbound texts and a sales team closes the order via SMS. For DTC brands where SMS is a real revenue channel, that combination is the moat.

Pricing has two components: a base monthly subscription ($0 starter with $49 minimum spend, $100 Growth, $500 Professional, custom Enterprise) and per-message rates ($0.007–$0.015/SMS, $0.024–$0.045/MMS) that drop with tier. Carrier fees apply on top, which surprises some operators. Postscript and Klaviyo SMS are the two serious choices for Shopify brands; Postscript wins on SMS-native depth, Klaviyo wins on email + SMS unification.', 'https://postscript.io', 'subscription', '[{"plan":"Starter","price":"$0/month base, $49 minimum monthly spend","features":["$0.015–$0.009/SMS, $0.045/MMS","Campaigns and automations","Unlimited segments","Dedicated toll-free number","2 opt-in keywords"]},{"plan":"Growth","price":"$100/month","features":["$0.01–$0.008/SMS, $0.03/MMS","Unlimited opt-in keywords","Live chat and email support","All Starter features"]},{"plan":"Professional","price":"$500/month","features":["$0.007/SMS, $0.024/MMS","Enhanced analytics","Priority support","API access","Removal of Powered by Postscript branding"]},{"plan":"Enterprise","price":"Custom","features":["Onboarding specialist","Personalised AI message recommendations","Priority support","Data warehouse push"]}]'::jsonb, 'beginner', true, '{"web","api"}', '{"Shopify-native event and order data","Opt-in capture (popups, checkout, keywords, landing pages)","Visual flow builder with built-in templates","Abandoned cart, browse, post-purchase, win-back flows","Two-way conversational SMS","Postscript Sales — human-in-the-loop SMS sales team","Segmentation on Shopify orders and customer attributes","Quiet hours and TCPA compliance","Toll-free, short-code, and 10DLC numbers","A/B testing on copy and send time","Revenue attribution tied to Shopify"}', '{"Shopify","Klaviyo","Recharge","Yotpo","Gorgias","Zendesk","Attentive","Stamped","Smile.io","Shopify Flow"}', true, '{"Shopify brands where SMS is a meaningful revenue channel","DTC brands with strong list-growth and existing email program","Teams running conversational sales (textbacks, VIP concierge)","Brands hitting the limits of Klaviyo SMS"}', '{"Non-Shopify stores (BigCommerce, Magento — Postscript is Shopify-first)","Brands without a working email program (start there first)","Markets with strict SMS opt-in regulation outside US/CA without legal review"}', 'The Shopify SMS specialist. If SMS is a top-three revenue channel, Postscript usually beats Klaviyo SMS on depth and conversational features; if SMS is a side channel, just use Klaviyo.', '{"https://help.postscript.io/"}', 'Per-message rates plus carrier fees plus the monthly base mean blended SMS cost is higher than the headline pricing implies — model your full cost before committing. Shopify-only — BigCommerce and Magento support is thin to none. Dedicated short codes cost $750/month on top of the platform fee. International SMS support is improving but US/Canada is still where the product shines. The value gap vs Klaviyo SMS narrows for brands that do not need conversational sales — for plain campaign-and-flow SMS, Klaviyo is often good enough and consolidates the bill.', '{}', '{"reddit_threads":[]}'::jsonb, '{"Run an SMS-first abandoned cart flow that triggers within minutes of cart abandonment.","Build a VIP concierge program where high-CLV customers text a real human for product recommendations.","A/B test SMS copy and send time on a Black Friday campaign with full Shopify revenue attribution.","Capture SMS opt-ins via Shopify checkout and post-purchase, syncing with Klaviyo email."}', 'Sweet spot: a Shopify DTC brand at $1M–$50M/year where SMS is already a meaningful revenue line and the team is willing to operate conversational features (Postscript Sales, two-way replies). The Shopify-native data plus the conversational layer is what justifies the premium over Klaviyo SMS.

Failure modes. Brands sign up for Postscript, treat it like a one-way blast tool, and never touch the conversational features. At that point you are paying a premium for capabilities you are not using — Klaviyo SMS would be cheaper and good enough. The other failure is opt-in cost: aggressive popup-based list growth on a small base produces a list that does not respond well, and SMS unsubscribes burn list value faster than email. Carrier filtering on toll-free numbers can also cause silent delivery issues that go unnoticed for weeks.

What to pilot. Run Postscript on Growth tier ($100/mo) for 60 days against your top three SMS use cases (abandoned cart, post-purchase, one Black Friday-style campaign). Track revenue per SMS and SMS-attributed revenue against your prior tool or against Klaviyo SMS. If Postscript drives ≥20% more revenue per send and your team uses the conversational features at least once per week, the investment is real; if not, consolidate into Klaviyo and save the bill.', now())
,
('FreshBooks', 'freshbooks', 'Cloud accounting and invoicing built for freelancers and service-based small businesses.', 'FreshBooks is a cloud accounting platform that started as an invoicing tool for freelancers and grew into a full small-business accounting suite. The product is opinionated for service businesses — consultants, agencies, contractors, lawyers, designers — rather than retail or inventory-heavy operations. That focus shows in the UI: invoicing, time tracking, project profitability, and client retainers are first-class, while inventory and manufacturing modules are intentionally absent.

Where FreshBooks differentiates from QuickBooks: it is genuinely easier to onboard for a non-accountant. The dashboard speaks in plain English ("Outstanding Revenue", "Profit"), invoice creation takes a minute, and the mobile app is a real working tool rather than a bolted-on companion. Where it loses to QuickBooks: accountant ecosystem depth, third-party integration breadth, and inventory features are weaker — if you sell physical products, FreshBooks will fight you.

The platform has added AI features incrementally — receipt scanning via the mobile app, automatic expense categorization, and bill-extraction from email — but these are convenience layers on top of a traditional accounting product, not the core pitch. Most users pick FreshBooks because the invoicing-and-time-tracking workflow fits their service business, then keep it because the books stay clean without much fuss.

It runs as a subscription with four tiers from Lite ($6.90/mo for 5 clients) to Select (custom enterprise pricing). The 70% off four months promo is essentially permanent. There is a public REST API, an app marketplace with hundreds of integrations, and accountant collaboration tools.', 'https://freshbooks.com', 'subscription', '[{"plan":"Lite","price":"$6.90/mo (intro) / $21/mo standard","features":["5 billable clients","Unlimited invoices and estimates","Time tracking and expenses","Basic tax reporting","Mobile app with mileage tracking"]},{"plan":"Plus","price":"$12.90/mo (intro) / $38/mo standard","features":["50 billable clients","Recurring invoices and client retainers","Proposals","Double-entry accounting reports","Accountant access"]},{"plan":"Premium","price":"$21/mo (intro) / $65/mo standard","features":["Unlimited billable clients","Project profitability tracking","Customisable email templates","Advanced bill receipt scanning","Accounts payable workflow"]},{"plan":"Select","price":"Custom","features":["Dedicated account manager","Lower payment processing fees","2 team members included","Migration assistance","Premium phone support"]}]'::jsonb, 'beginner', true, '{"web","api","mobile"}', '{"Invoicing with online payments and auto-reminders","Time tracking with billable conversion","Expense capture and receipt scanning (mobile)","Project profitability reporting","Client retainers and recurring invoices","Proposals and estimates","Double-entry accounting and chart of accounts","Bank feeds and reconciliation","Mileage tracking","Accountant collaboration and journal entries","Public REST API and Zapier"}', '{"Stripe","PayPal","Gusto","Zapier","Mailchimp","HubSpot","Shopify","Squarespace","Slack","Google Workspace","Microsoft 365","Bench"}', true, '{"Freelancers and solopreneurs who bill hourly or by project","Service agencies under 10 people","Consultants and contractors who need invoice-first accounting","Non-accountants who want clean books without a learning curve"}', '{"Inventory-heavy retailers (use QuickBooks or Xero)","Multi-entity holding companies","Businesses that already have a QuickBooks-trained accountant in-house","Manufacturing or e-commerce with complex COGS"}', 'The right pick if you are a service business that bills time or projects and wants accounting that stays out of your way. Lose to QuickBooks on integration depth and inventory; win on invoicing UX and onboarding speed.', '{"https://www.freshbooks.com/support"}', 'Standard pricing after the intro period is meaningfully higher than the headline rates — Lite jumps to $21/mo, Premium to $65/mo, and the difference compounds over a year. Inventory and multi-currency support are thinner than Xero or QuickBooks. The accountant ecosystem is smaller — many accountants prefer QuickBooks files. Payroll is via a Gusto integration rather than native, which adds a separate bill. AI features (receipt scan, categorization) are incremental, not category-leading.', '{}', '{"reddit_threads":[]}'::jsonb, '{"Send a branded invoice and get paid via Stripe in one click.","Convert tracked time on a client project directly into a billable invoice.","See real-time project profitability across labour, expenses, and invoiced amount.","Set up retainer-based monthly billing for ongoing client work.","Capture a receipt with the mobile app and have it auto-categorised against an expense account."}', 'Sweet spot: a service business with one to ten people that bills clients (hourly, fixed-fee, or retainer) and does not want to think about accounting more than once a month. The invoicing flow is the best in the small-business category, and the books behind it are clean enough that a part-time accountant can close the year without drama.

Failure modes to know about. The headline pricing is intro-only — model your year-two cost at the standard rate before committing. If you sell physical products, expect to outgrow FreshBooks within a year; the inventory module is functional but not a long-term home for a real e-commerce or retail business. If your accountant is QuickBooks-native, switching them costs goodwill — ask first.

What to pilot. Run FreshBooks alongside your current system for one month: send 5 real invoices, capture 20 receipts, reconcile your bank feed, and run the month-end profit-and-loss. If the workflow feels lighter and the numbers match your existing books, it will hold up at scale. Treat the AI features as nice-to-haves, not the reason to switch — the core value is the invoicing-first accounting workflow.', now()),
('Wave', 'wave', 'Free accounting and invoicing for very small businesses, with paid payroll and bookkeeping add-ons.', 'Wave is one of the few accounting products with a genuinely free tier — not a 30-day trial, but a working accounting and invoicing app you can run a small business on indefinitely. The Starter plan covers unlimited invoices, estimates, bills, and double-entry bookkeeping at no monthly cost. Wave makes its money on payment processing fees (2.9% + $0.60 per card, similar to Stripe) and on paid add-ons: payroll, bookkeeping advisory, and the Pro plan that adds bank feeds and receipt automation.

Architecturally Wave is closest to FreshBooks for the freelancer / very-small-business segment, but it trades polish and integration depth for being free. If your business is small enough that you can manually import bank transactions or live without auto-categorization, the Starter plan is hard to argue with. The moment you want bank feeds, automated reminders, or branded invoices you are on the $19/mo Pro plan, where Wave starts looking like every other paid alternative.

The Wave Advisors program ($199+/mo) is the differentiator most people miss — it pairs you with a dedicated bookkeeper who lives inside your Wave account and does monthly reconciliation, statements, and tax prep. For a sole proprietor who wants real bookkeeping help without a full accountant retainer, this is genuinely competitive with hiring a part-time bookkeeper directly.

Wave was acquired by H&R Block in 2019 and continues to operate as an independent product line. AI is incremental — receipt OCR on the Pro plan, auto-categorization on transactions — not the product.', 'https://waveapps.com', 'freemium', '[{"plan":"Starter","price":"Free","features":["Unlimited invoices, estimates, bills","Double-entry bookkeeping","Manual transaction import","Mobile app","Card processing 2.9% + $0.60"]},{"plan":"Pro","price":"$19/mo (or $190/year)","features":["Auto-import bank transactions","Auto-merge and categorize","Unlimited receipt capture","Branded invoices","Late payment auto-reminders","Add multiple users"]},{"plan":"Wave Advisors","price":"From $199/mo","features":["Dedicated bookkeeper","Monthly reconciliation and statements","Includes Pro features","Tax prep guidance","Email and phone support"]},{"plan":"Payroll","price":"$20-$40/mo + $6/employee","features":["Self-service or full-service payroll","Direct deposit","Tax filings (full-service in supported states)","Employee self-onboarding"]}]'::jsonb, 'beginner', false, '{"web","mobile"}', '{"Free unlimited invoicing and estimates","Double-entry bookkeeping (free tier)","Bank feeds and auto-categorization (Pro)","Receipt capture and OCR (Pro)","Recurring billing","Online payments via Wave Payments","Payroll add-on (US and Canada)","Bookkeeping advisor add-on","Sales tax tracking","Multi-business support under one login"}', '{"Stripe","Etsy","PayPal","Shoeboxed","Zapier (limited)","Bank feeds via Plaid","H&R Block tax filing"}', true, '{"Solo freelancers and side-hustles on a tight budget","Very small businesses that send <50 invoices a month","Sole proprietors who want a free entry-level bookkeeping tool","Microbusinesses needing managed bookkeeping cheaply via Advisors"}', '{"Multi-employee companies that need deep payroll","Inventory-heavy retailers","Businesses that need third-party integrations beyond payments","Teams expecting a public REST API (Wave does not publish one)"}', 'The strongest free accounting product on the market, with a genuine path to a managed-bookkeeping service. Outgrow it within 1-2 years if you scale, but the Starter plan is rare honest value.', '{"https://support.waveapps.com/hc/en-us"}', 'No public REST API — third-party integrations are limited to a handful of partners and Zapier connectors. Payroll is US/Canada only and full-service tax filing is restricted to a subset of US states. The Pro plan removes most free-tier pain points but at $19/mo plus payment processing it stops being meaningfully cheaper than FreshBooks Lite. Inventory features are bare-bones. Customer support on the free tier is community-only.', '{}', '{"reddit_threads":[]}'::jsonb, '{"Run a side-hustle business with under 30 invoices a month, paying $0 in software.","Send a branded recurring invoice and accept ACH or card payment online.","Capture a coffee receipt on the mobile app and have it categorised to ''Meals''.","Hand off monthly reconciliation to a Wave Advisor while keeping the books in one place.","Pay one or two W-2 employees through the integrated payroll add-on."}', 'Sweet spot: a sole proprietor or side-business that needs real double-entry bookkeeping but legitimately cannot justify $20+/mo for software. Wave Starter does the job, and the upgrade path to Pro or Advisors is gradual rather than punitive. For freelancers who hate accounting, the Advisors tier is the underrated buy — cheaper than a local bookkeeper, with the books living inside the same tool.

Failure modes. The free plan loses its shine the moment you want bank feeds: at that point you are paying for Pro, and Pro''s feature set is narrower than a same-priced FreshBooks or QuickBooks Simple Start. The lack of an API matters more than people expect — once you want to push data to a CRM or BI tool, you are exporting CSVs. Payroll is fine for 1-3 employees in supported states; outside that envelope, Gusto or QuickBooks Payroll will serve you better.

What to pilot. Run a single month on the free Starter plan: send your real invoices, manually import a bank statement, and reconcile. If the manual import does not annoy you and your invoice volume is under 30 a month, you have a permanent home. If you find yourself wanting bank feeds within a week, price-compare Wave Pro against FreshBooks Lite before committing — at $19/mo the differences come down to UX and integration needs, not features.', now()),
('Xero', 'xero', 'Cloud accounting platform built for small businesses and the accountants who serve them.', 'Xero is a cloud accounting platform headquartered in New Zealand that became the dominant SMB accounting tool in Australia, New Zealand, and the UK before expanding into the US. Architecturally it is a peer of QuickBooks Online — full double-entry accounting, bank feeds, payroll, inventory, multi-currency, project tracking, and a deep app marketplace — but it is built around a different operating principle. Xero charges per organisation rather than per user, so unlimited team members and unlimited accountant collaboration are included in every plan. That alone changes how SMBs structure their finance function.

In non-US markets, Xero is often the default choice over QuickBooks. The product handles GST/VAT, multi-currency, and country-specific payroll natively rather than as bolt-ons, and the accountant ecosystem outside the US treats Xero as a first-class citizen. Inside the US, QuickBooks still has more accountants trained on it and a wider third-party integration footprint, which is why Xero is more often seen at tech-forward SMBs and accountants who specifically chose against QuickBooks.

The 2026 pricing restructure renamed Early/Growing/Established to Starter/Standard/Premium and dropped prices: $20 / $47 / $80 per month respectively (US). The Starter plan caps at 20 invoices and 5 bills per month, which is restrictive — most businesses move to Standard within months. Premium adds multi-currency, project tracking, and analytics.

AI features are incremental — predictive bank reconciliation, receipt scanning via Hubdoc (included), and anomaly detection — useful but not the core pitch. Xero is bought for the architecture (per-org pricing, accountant tooling, ecosystem) rather than the AI veneer.', 'https://xero.com', 'subscription', '[{"plan":"Starter (formerly Early)","price":"$20/mo (US)","features":["Send 20 invoices, enter 5 bills per month","Bank reconciliation","Hubdoc receipt capture","Mobile app","Unlimited users"]},{"plan":"Standard (formerly Growing)","price":"$47/mo (US)","features":["Unlimited invoices and bills","Bulk reconcile","Short-term cash flow snapshot","Multi-currency view of accounts (limited)","All Starter features"]},{"plan":"Premium (formerly Established)","price":"$80/mo (US)","features":["Multi-currency accounting","Expenses module","Project tracking and profitability","Advanced analytics (Analytics Plus)","All Standard features"]}]'::jsonb, 'intermediate', true, '{"web","api","mobile"}', '{"Double-entry accounting with bank feeds","Unlimited users on every plan","Multi-currency (Premium)","Project tracking and time billing","Inventory tracking","Hubdoc receipt and bill capture (included)","Predictive bank reconciliation","Quote-to-invoice workflow","Public REST API and OAuth 2.0","1,000+ app marketplace integrations","Accountant collaboration tools","Country-specific payroll (AU/NZ/UK; US via Gusto integration)"}', '{"Stripe","PayPal","Gusto","HubSpot","Shopify","Square","WooCommerce","Hubdoc","Salesforce","Slack","Google Workspace","Microsoft 365","Plaid","Wise"}', true, '{"SMBs in AU, NZ, UK, and tech-forward US businesses","Multi-entity or multi-currency operations","Service businesses with project profitability needs","Accountants serving 10+ clients (AU/NZ/UK ecosystem)","Teams that need unlimited user seats"}', '{"US sole proprietors who already have a QuickBooks-trained accountant","Businesses needing the deepest US-specific payroll (use QuickBooks)","Very small businesses under 5 invoices a month (Wave is free)"}', 'The right cloud accounting platform if you are outside the US, or inside the US and willing to pay a small ecosystem tax for cleaner architecture and unlimited users. QuickBooks still wins on US accountant availability.', '{"https://central.xero.com/s/"}', 'Starter plan limits (20 invoices, 5 bills) are tight enough that most businesses move to Standard within a quarter. US payroll requires the Gusto integration as a separate subscription. Multi-currency is Premium-only. Inventory is functional but not a fit for high-SKU retailers. US accountant pool is smaller than QuickBooks, which can slow tax season. AI features are present but trail brand AI tools by a wide margin.', '{}', '{"reddit_threads":[]}'::jsonb, '{"Run multi-entity bookkeeping with unlimited users at no per-seat cost.","Reconcile a quarter of bank transactions in an afternoon using bulk match.","Track a fixed-fee project across labour, expenses, and revenue with profitability reporting.","Hand a fully shared file to your accountant without paying for an extra seat.","Operate a multi-currency consultancy with USD, GBP, and EUR clients in one ledger."}', 'Sweet spot: a small or mid-sized business outside the US, or a tech-aware US SMB whose accountant is comfortable with Xero. The unlimited-users model is the underrated win — you stop rationing seats and just give finance, ops, and the founder all proper access. Multi-currency is the second underrated win for any business with a single non-domestic client.

Failure modes. In the US, the smaller accountant pool is real friction. If your CPA learned QuickBooks 15 years ago and has no Xero clients, the cost of switching them outweighs Xero''s architectural advantages — pick QuickBooks. The Starter plan''s invoice cap will bite faster than you expect — budget for Standard from day one if you bill more than 20 customers a month. Treat the AI features as quality-of-life upgrades, not a reason to choose Xero over a competitor.

What to pilot. Migrate one quarter of historic data, run a month of live transactions, and ask your accountant to close the books in Xero. If they can do it in the same time as your current tool, the architectural wins compound. If they fight the interface, the friction will compound the other way and you should stay on QuickBooks. Test the multi-currency module specifically if you have any non-domestic invoicing — it is one of Xero''s genuine differentiators.', now()),
('QuickBooks', 'quickbooks', 'Intuit cloud accounting — the de facto standard for US small businesses and the accountants who serve them.', 'QuickBooks Online is the dominant cloud accounting platform in the US small-business market and one of Intuit''s flagship products alongside TurboTax and Mailchimp. Architecturally it is a peer of Xero — full double-entry accounting, bank feeds, payroll, inventory, projects, multi-currency, an enormous app marketplace, and a public API — but its real moat is the accountant ecosystem. The vast majority of US accountants and bookkeepers are QuickBooks-trained, which means at tax time you have a near-infinite supply of professionals who can take over your books without any re-tooling.

The four-tier US lineup runs Simple Start ($38/mo, 1 user), Essentials ($75/mo, 3 users), Plus ($115/mo, 5 users with inventory and project tracking), and Advanced ($275/mo, 25 users with custom reporting and dedicated support). Pricing has crept up substantially over the last few years — the same Plus plan was $90 in 2023 — and Intuit''s upgrade pressure inside the product is steady. Each tier adds a meaningful capability rather than just user seats: Essentials unlocks bill management, Plus unlocks inventory and projects, Advanced unlocks custom roles and analytics.

QuickBooks Online has been adding AI features aggressively under the "Intuit Assist" banner — auto-categorization, anomaly flags, cash flow forecasting, an in-app assistant for invoicing and expense queries. The features are competent but evolving fast and the marketing oversells them; treat them as quality-of-life improvements on top of a traditional accounting product, not as the core reason to buy.

Outside cost, QuickBooks'' main weakness is value-per-dollar at the higher tiers. Plus and Advanced are expensive relative to comparable Xero plans, and Intuit''s frequent price increases have pushed cost-conscious SMBs toward alternatives — but the accountant lock-in keeps most users in place anyway.', 'https://quickbooks.intuit.com', 'subscription', '[{"plan":"Simple Start","price":"$38/mo","features":["1 user","Income and expense tracking","Send invoices and accept payments","Bank feeds","Mileage tracking","Basic reports","Tax deduction capture"]},{"plan":"Essentials","price":"$75/mo","features":["3 users","Bill management and pay","Time tracking","Multi-currency","Enhanced reports","All Simple Start features"]},{"plan":"Plus","price":"$115/mo","features":["5 users","Inventory tracking","Project profitability","Class and location tracking","1099 contractor management","All Essentials features"]},{"plan":"Advanced","price":"$275/mo","features":["25 users","Custom user roles","Workflow automation","Custom reports (Spreadsheet Sync, Fathom)","Dedicated account team","Premium app integrations","All Plus features"]}]'::jsonb, 'intermediate', true, '{"web","api","mobile","desktop"}', '{"Double-entry accounting with bank feeds","Invoicing and payment processing","Bill pay and accounts payable","Inventory and SKU tracking (Plus+)","Project profitability","Multi-currency (Essentials+)","Class and location tracking (Plus+)","Mileage and receipt capture (mobile)","QuickBooks Payroll add-on (US)","Public REST API and OAuth","Intuit Assist AI features (auto-categorize, anomaly flags, cash flow)","750+ app marketplace integrations","Accountant collaboration"}', '{"Stripe","PayPal","Square","Shopify","Amazon","eBay","HubSpot","Salesforce","Slack","Gusto","TSheets","Bill.com","Plaid","Mailchimp"}', true, '{"US small businesses of any size that want accountant interoperability","Inventory-heavy retailers and e-commerce","Multi-entity SMBs needing class/location tracking","Service businesses on Plus tier for project profitability","Companies that need US payroll integrated natively"}', '{"Cost-conscious freelancers (Wave or FreshBooks Lite are cheaper)","Non-US businesses (Xero is usually a better fit)","Teams that resent vendor lock-in and Intuit''s upgrade pressure","Very simple businesses that only need invoicing"}', 'The default US small-business accounting platform. You are buying the accountant ecosystem and integration depth as much as the software — both are best-in-class. Cost is the main argument against.', '{"https://quickbooks.intuit.com/learn-support/"}', 'Pricing has risen sharply year over year — model the standard rate, not the intro discount. Per-user limits are tight (Plus caps at 5 users; jumping to Advanced at $275/mo for the 6th user is steep). Intuit Assist AI features are still maturing; the marketing runs ahead of the product. Inventory works for moderate SKU counts but high-volume retailers will outgrow it. Customer support quality varies — phone wait times spike during tax season. Vendor lock-in is real once a year of historical data lives in the platform.', '{}', '{"reddit_threads":[]}'::jsonb, '{"Send invoices, accept ACH and card payments, and reconcile in one workflow.","Track inventory across multiple warehouses with reorder points (Plus tier).","Manage 1099 contractors and file year-end forms directly through the platform.","Run native US payroll with tax filings included via the QuickBooks Payroll add-on.","Hand a clean, accountant-friendly file to a CPA at year-end — the path most US accountants prefer."}', 'Sweet spot: a US small business that expects to work with an outside accountant or bookkeeper at some point and wants the path of least resistance. QuickBooks is rarely the cheapest option and rarely the prettiest, but the accountant interoperability and integration breadth pay off the moment you hit a complex situation — multi-state tax, an audit, an acquisition, or just a finance hire who needs to ramp quickly.

Failure modes. Two big ones. First, the upgrade staircase: Simple Start to Essentials to Plus is a real cost climb, and Intuit''s product UI will nudge you upward at every opportunity. Pick the tier that matches a 12-month outlook, not your current month. Second, the AI features marketing is louder than the underlying capability — auto-categorization is fine, anomaly detection misses obvious ones, and the assistant is useful for simple queries but not transformative. Do not pay extra for AI; pay for the accounting platform.

What to pilot. If your current accountant is QuickBooks-native, the decision is mostly made — pilot mostly to choose between Simple Start, Essentials, and Plus by mapping your real workflow (do you have bills to pay? inventory? projects?). If your accountant is open to either tool, run a parallel month on QuickBooks and Xero on the same dataset and see which feels less hostile. The platform you stay on for five years matters more than which one wins this quarter.', now()),
('Expensify', 'expensify', 'Expense management with receipt scanning, corporate cards, and travel — designed to remove the expense report.', 'Expensify is an expense-management platform that built its reputation on SmartScan — a receipt-scanning OCR pipeline that extracts merchant, amount, date, and category from a photo and turns it into a coded expense line. Around that core it has built a full expense-management product: corporate cards (the Expensify Card), reimbursement workflows, multi-level approval policies, mileage tracking, travel booking, and tight integrations with QuickBooks, Xero, NetSuite, Sage Intacct, and FinancialForce.

Where Expensify fits in a finance stack: it sits between corporate spend and the general ledger, replacing the manual expense-report cycle. Employees photograph receipts; SmartScan codes them; policies flag violations; managers approve; the system pushes coded transactions into your accounting platform and reimburses via ACH. For companies that have outgrown emailed receipts and shared spreadsheets, this collapses days of admin into minutes.

Pricing was overhauled in April 2025 to a flat per-member model. Collect runs $5/member/month for SMB-grade features (basic policies, SmartScan, accounting sync, reimbursement). Control runs $9/member/month with advanced approval workflows, custom roles, audit trails, and corporate-card reconciliation — but only if you adopt the Expensify Card; without the card, Control jumps to $18/month annual or $36/month month-to-month. The card-tied pricing model is intentional — Expensify monetises interchange and discounts software accordingly.

AI features are real and incremental: SmartScan is the original AI feature in this category, and Expensify has added concierge-style chat, automated policy violation explanations, and merchant categorization improvements. None of this makes Expensify primarily an "AI tool" — it is an expense-management product that uses AI in places where it removes admin work.', 'https://expensify.com', 'subscription', '[{"plan":"Free Trial","price":"Free","features":["Try Expensify Card","Basic SmartScan","Limited reports","Single user"]},{"plan":"Collect","price":"$5/member/mo (with Expensify Card)","features":["Unlimited SmartScan","Approval workflows","Reimbursement via ACH","QuickBooks / Xero / NetSuite sync","Corporate card reconciliation","Mobile app"]},{"plan":"Control","price":"$9/member/mo (with Expensify Card; $18 annual or $36 m2m without card)","features":["Advanced approval workflows","Custom roles","Audit trails","Multi-level GL coding","NetSuite and Sage Intacct deep integration","SAML SSO"]},{"plan":"Expensify Card","price":"Bundled","features":["Corporate card with cashback","Realtime reconciliation","Spend controls","Issue virtual or physical cards"]}]'::jsonb, 'beginner', true, '{"web","api","mobile"}', '{"SmartScan receipt OCR (proprietary)","Mobile app with receipt photo upload","Expensify Card (corporate card with reconciliation)","Multi-level approval workflows","Reimbursement via ACH","Mileage tracking","Travel booking (Expensify Travel)","Real-time accounting sync (QB, Xero, NetSuite, Sage Intacct, FinancialForce)","Custom roles and audit trails (Control)","Public REST API","Concierge chat-based support","Policy violation flags"}', '{"QuickBooks Online","QuickBooks Desktop","Xero","NetSuite","Sage Intacct","FinancialForce","Workday","Gusto","ADP","SAP","Slack","Microsoft Teams","Plaid"}', true, '{"SMBs and mid-market companies replacing manual expense reports","Distributed teams whose finance team cannot chase paper receipts","Companies adopting corporate cards and wanting one-click reconciliation","Finance teams using QuickBooks, Xero, NetSuite, or Sage Intacct"}', '{"Solo freelancers (overkill — use the FreshBooks or Wave receipt feature)","Companies that strictly forbid third-party fintech card programs","Buyers who want truly card-agnostic pricing (Control without card is expensive)","Enterprises needing per-country compliance beyond US/UK/AU"}', 'The default expense-management tool for SMBs and mid-market companies on cloud accounting. Pricing only makes sense once you adopt the Expensify Card — without it, the ROI conversation gets harder.', '{"https://help.expensify.com/"}', 'Card-tied pricing penalises companies that prefer existing corporate cards (Brex, Ramp, AmEx) — Control without the Expensify Card is $18/member/month annual or $36 month-to-month, which puts it above competitors. SmartScan is excellent but not perfect; expect a small percentage of receipts to need manual correction. International expense and tax handling is solid for US/UK/AU but thinner elsewhere. Concierge AI chat is helpful for support but is not a transformative agent. Brex and Ramp bundle expense management free with their cards, which has eroded Expensify''s pricing leverage in startup-land.', '{}', '{"reddit_threads":[]}'::jsonb, '{"Replace a manual expense-report cycle so employees just photograph receipts and finance auto-codes them.","Issue corporate cards to a distributed team and reconcile in real time against the general ledger.","Enforce a multi-level approval policy on expenses above a threshold (manager + finance).","Push fully-coded expense transactions to NetSuite or Sage Intacct without manual journal entries.","Run a monthly close where T&E reconciliation takes hours instead of days."}', 'Sweet spot: an SMB or mid-market company with 20-500 employees that has outgrown spreadsheet-based expense reports, runs cloud accounting (QuickBooks, Xero, NetSuite, or Sage Intacct), and is comfortable adopting a corporate card program. With the Expensify Card the per-member math works out — $5/member/month is competitive, and the time saved on receipt chasing pays back quickly.

Failure modes. The biggest is buying Control without the Expensify Card and being shocked by the $18/member/month price tag at renewal — model the card-versus-no-card cost upfront. The second is comparing against Brex and Ramp, which give expense management free with their corporate cards; if you are happy with their card programs, Expensify''s software-only value gets harder to justify. The third is assuming SmartScan is 100% accurate — it is excellent but expense policies should still review flagged items.

What to pilot. Run a 30-day trial across one team (10-20 people) with real expense flow. Measure the time-per-expense-report before and after, the SmartScan accuracy on your specific merchant mix, and the friction of accounting sync to your GL. If the time-saved math is double the per-member fee and your finance team stops chasing receipts, scale company-wide; if Brex or Ramp could give you the same workflow inside their card product, take that path instead.', now()),
('Deel', 'deel', 'Global payroll, contractor management, and Employer of Record across 150+ countries.', 'Deel is the category-defining platform for hiring and paying people across borders. The product spans three core motions: contractor management (compliant agreements, multi-currency invoicing, tax forms in 120+ currencies), Employer of Record (Deel acts as the legal employer in 110+ countries so you can hire without setting up an entity), and global payroll (running payroll across your own entities with local tax, statutory filings, and benefits handled by Deel''s in-country teams).

Deel''s main competition is Remote, Oyster, Velocity Global, and Multiplier on the EOR side; Papaya Global and ADP Celergo on multi-country payroll; and a long tail of point tools (Wise, Plane, Letsdeel''s old contractor lane) on contractor pay. Deel''s edge is breadth — it has more country coverage and ships features faster than rivals — and an aggressive pricing position on contractors ($49/contractor/month is below most competitors). The flip side: depth varies by country, and Deel has been criticized for support quality at the long tail of geographies where it has fewer in-country specialists.

In 2024–2026 Deel layered "Deel AI" on top: an in-app assistant that answers questions about contracts, expenses, country-specific compliance, and payroll variances. It''s a useful retrieval layer over Deel''s own data and country knowledge base — not a transformative product change. The AI feature is the kind of thing every HR-tech vendor shipped this cycle; treat it as a small efficiency boost, not the reason to buy Deel.

The platform also includes Deel HR (free HRIS for any team using Deel for payroll/EOR), Deel IT (device provisioning and offboarding), Deel Engage (performance and learning), and Deel Immigration (visa support). Bundling has gotten dense — most teams start with one product and grow into the suite.', 'https://deel.com', 'paid', '[{"plan":"Contractors","price":"$49/contractor/month","features":["Compliant contracts in 150+ countries","Multi-currency payments (120+ currencies)","Automated invoicing and tax forms","Free Deel HR included"]},{"plan":"EOR Standard","price":"$599/employee/month","features":["Full legal employment in 110+ countries","Automated onboarding and compliance","Managed payroll, tax filings, and benefits","Localized contracts"]},{"plan":"EOR Premium","price":"$899/employee/month","features":["Everything in Standard","Dedicated onboarding manager","Legal response guarantees","SSO/SAML and dedicated support"]},{"plan":"Global Payroll","price":"$29/employee/month","features":["Local tax and statutory filing","Multi-currency payroll","Self-service portals","In-country payroll specialists"]},{"plan":"US PEO","price":"From $125/employee/month","features":["Payroll across all 50 states","Federal, state, local tax handling","Group benefits access"]}]'::jsonb, 'beginner', true, '{"web","api","mobile"}', '{"Contractor management with compliant agreements","Employer of Record in 110+ countries","Global payroll across your own entities","US PEO and US payroll","Multi-currency contractor payments (120+ currencies)","Deel HR (free HRIS bundled with payroll/EOR)","Deel IT device provisioning and offboarding","Deel Engage (performance, learning, surveys)","Deel Immigration (visa and relocation support)","Deel AI in-app assistant for contracts and compliance Q&A","Expense management and reimbursements","Background checks","Equity and stock option administration"}', '{"QuickBooks","Xero","NetSuite","BambooHR","Workday","Greenhouse","Lever","Ashby","Slack","Microsoft Teams","Okta","Google Workspace","Workato","Zapier"}', true, '{"Startups hiring their first international contractors or employees","Scale-ups expanding into new countries without setting up entities","Companies running payroll across many entities who want a single platform","Remote-first teams that need one source of truth for global headcount"}', '{"US-only companies with simple payroll needs (Gusto / Rippling are cheaper)","Enterprises that already have country entities and prefer ADP / SAP SuccessFactors","Teams who only need contractor payments to a single country (Wise / direct bank is fine)"}', 'Deel is the default first choice for any company hiring across borders in 2026 — broadest country coverage, fastest feature shipping, aggressive contractor pricing. Just budget for the EOR markup if you go that route long-term.', '{"https://help.letsdeel.com/hc/en-gb"}', 'EOR pricing ($599+ per employee per month) becomes the wrong economic choice once you have 5+ employees in one country — at that point setting up your own entity and using Deel Global Payroll is materially cheaper. Country support depth varies; the top 30 countries get fast, deep service while the long tail can be slower. The Deel AI assistant is a thin overlay on Deel''s own knowledge base — useful for FAQ-style questions, not a substitute for an HR business partner. Past press cycles flagged compliance and worker-classification disputes; do your own diligence on contractor-vs-employee classification in your target countries.', '{}', '{"reddit_threads":[]}'::jsonb, '{"Hire your first engineer in Portugal without setting up a Portuguese entity.","Pay 50 contractors across 25 countries from a single dashboard each month.","Run payroll across your US, UK, and German entities through one platform.","Onboard a new EOR hire with localized contract, benefits enrollment, and equipment shipping in one flow."}', 'Sweet spot: a 20–500-person company hiring globally where you don''t have entities in most of your target countries. Deel''s contractor product at $49/month is genuinely best-in-class on price and breadth. The EOR product is competitive when you have 1–4 employees per country; once you cross five, do the math on setting up your own entity.

Failure modes. Teams sometimes treat EOR as a permanent state when it should be a 6–18 month bridge — at scale, the per-head markup adds up to real money. Country coverage is wide but not uniform; verify that your specific target country has solid in-country support before you commit a hire there. Deel AI is a nice-to-have, not a buying reason — the actual product is the operational platform underneath. And the bundle drift is real: starting with Contractors and ending up paying for HR, IT, and Engage is a common path; review your line items annually.

What to pilot. Start with the product you most need (usually Contractors or EOR for one or two hires). Run it for 60 days end-to-end — onboarding, invoicing, payment, support tickets — and judge based on real operational quality, not the demo. If support quality holds up in your specific countries, expand from there.', now()),
('Rippling', 'rippling', 'Unified HR, IT, and finance platform that runs your workforce off a single employee record.', 'Rippling''s pitch is structural rather than feature-driven: one employee record powers HR, IT, and Finance, so onboarding a new hire automatically provisions payroll, benefits, devices, app access, corporate cards, and expense policies in a single flow. Offboarding reverses all of it. The architecture is the product — every other HRIS bolts these pieces together with integrations; Rippling owns the graph natively.

Direct competition: Workday and SAP SuccessFactors at the enterprise end, BambooHR and Gusto at the SMB end, and Deel for global. Rippling''s wedge is the IT and Finance modules — no other HRIS has device management, identity (SSO), corporate cards, expense, and bill pay as first-class products on the same platform. For a 50–2,000 person company that wants to consolidate HR, IT, and spend on one vendor, the consolidation story is genuinely differentiated.

Pricing is opaque — Rippling does not publish per-module pricing publicly. Industry-reported starting points are roughly $8–$12/employee/month for the core HR platform, with each additional module (Payroll, Benefits, Device Management, Identity, Corporate Card, Expense, Bill Pay, Global Payroll, Learning) adding incrementally. Real total cost depends on which modules you turn on and your headcount; expect $35–$80/employee/month all-in for a fully-loaded mid-market deployment.

Rippling has shipped AI features (workflow studio with AI-assisted automation, an in-app AI search and Q&A assistant) but, like its peers, this is overlay on top of an established platform. The reason to buy Rippling is the unified-record architecture — the AI is incremental.', 'https://rippling.com', 'subscription', '[{"plan":"Rippling Platform (core)","price":"From ~$8/employee/month","features":["Employee record + workflow engine","Org chart and permissions","Reporting","Required base for any module"]},{"plan":"HR modules (Payroll, Benefits, Time, Talent)","price":"Add-on per module","features":["US payroll","Benefits administration","Time tracking","Recruiting and ATS","Performance and learning"]},{"plan":"IT modules (Device, Identity, Inventory)","price":"Add-on per module","features":["MDM for Mac/Windows","SSO and SCIM provisioning","Device inventory and shipping","App access management"]},{"plan":"Finance modules (Spend, Bill Pay, Corporate Card)","price":"Add-on per module","features":["Corporate cards","Expense management","Bill pay","Spend policies and approvals"]},{"plan":"Enterprise / Global","price":"Custom","features":["Global payroll and EOR","Advanced security and compliance","Dedicated CSM","Custom contracts"]}]'::jsonb, 'intermediate', true, '{"web","api","mobile"}', '{"Unified employee record across HR, IT, and Finance","US and global payroll","Benefits administration and broker integration","Device management (MDM) for Mac and Windows","Identity / SSO / SCIM provisioning","Corporate cards and expense management","Bill pay","Headcount planning and reporting","Recruiting and ATS","Performance reviews and goals","Learning management","Workflow studio (custom automations across modules)","AI-assisted policy and workflow generation","Mobile app for managers and employees","Open API for custom integrations"}', '{"Slack","Microsoft Teams","Google Workspace","Microsoft 365","Salesforce","NetSuite","QuickBooks","Xero","Greenhouse","Lever","Ashby","Okta","Zapier","Workato"}', true, '{"50–2,000 person companies consolidating HR, IT, and finance vendors","Operationally heavy startups that want onboarding/offboarding to be one click","Finance teams that want corporate cards and expense on the same record as payroll","Multi-entity companies looking for one platform across HR + IT"}', '{"Sub-20-person teams (overkill — Gusto + a simple HRIS is cheaper)","Workday-committed enterprises (the migration cost rarely pencils out)","Companies that only need payroll (Gusto/ADP are simpler)","Buyers who require fully published pricing before pilot (Rippling is sales-led)"}', 'The most architecturally interesting HRIS on the market — the unified record is a real moat. Worth piloting any time you''re consolidating 3+ HR/IT/finance vendors.', '{"https://www.rippling.com/learn-more"}', 'Pricing is fully gated — you must talk to sales to get real numbers, and per-module list pricing is not published. Total cost ramps quickly as you add modules; the headline "from $8/employee/month" is just the platform, not a working configuration. Implementation is non-trivial — the unified record is powerful but takes weeks to set up correctly across HR, IT, and finance. Some modules (Recruiting, Learning) are less mature than dedicated point tools (Greenhouse, Lessonly). The AI features are useful overlays but not a buying reason.', '{}', '{"reddit_threads":[]}'::jsonb, '{"Onboard a new hire and have payroll, benefits, laptop shipping, SSO access, and corporate card all set up automatically.","Offboard a departing employee with one workflow that revokes app access, wipes the device, ends payroll, and closes the corporate card.","Build a custom workflow that ties promotion to a salary change, equity grant, and updated app permissions.","Consolidate Gusto + Justworks + Jamf + Okta + Brex onto a single platform."}', 'Sweet spot: a 50–500 person company that has accumulated 4+ HR/IT/finance vendors and is feeling the operational tax of stitching them together. Rippling''s consolidation story is real, and the unified employee record is genuinely a structural advantage over BambooHR, Gusto, and Workday — none of those own IT and Finance natively the way Rippling does.

Failure modes. Total cost is the most common surprise — the platform fee plus four or five modules adds up faster than buyers expect, and the sales-led pricing means you have to negotiate hard. Implementation discipline matters: badly configured modules feel worse than the standalone tools they replaced. Teams sometimes buy modules they don''t need because the bundling is convenient, then can''t justify the spend at renewal. And if you''re fully committed to Workday or fully happy with Gusto, the migration cost rarely pencils out unless you specifically need IT + Finance integration.

What to pilot. Pick two modules you genuinely need (commonly: Payroll + Device Management, or HR + Identity). Run the onboarding/offboarding flow for 5–10 real employees end-to-end. Measure (a) hours saved per onboarding, (b) implementation friction, (c) support quality on real tickets. If the unified-record story shows up in those three metrics, the rest of the modules will too. If not, the consolidation pitch is more marketing than reality for your context.', now()),
('Lattice', 'lattice', 'Performance management, engagement, and goals platform built for people-leader-driven companies.', 'Lattice is one of the two leaders in modern performance management software, alongside 15Five. The product covers the full performance stack: continuous feedback, 1:1 agendas, performance reviews (360, manager, peer, self), goals/OKRs, engagement surveys, career growth frameworks, and compensation reviews. The pitch is that you replace a patchwork of Google Docs, spreadsheets, and Culture Amp/SurveyMonkey with one integrated workflow.

Compared to 15Five, Lattice tends to be the choice of more "people-ops sophisticated" buyers — companies with a real Head of People who wants to design custom review cycles, calibrate at scale, and tie performance to compensation. 15Five leans more toward continuous-coaching workflows; Lattice leans more toward structured cycles. CultureAmp is the engagement-survey heavyweight, while Lattice''s engagement module is competent but less deep. Workday and SAP SuccessFactors are the enterprise alternatives — heavier, slower, but suited to >5,000-employee orgs.

Pricing is bundled and sales-led, with a published $4,000 minimum annual commitment and an unbundled $8/employee/month per-product list price (Performance, Goals, Engagement, etc, each priced separately). In practice most buyers commit to a multi-product bundle and negotiate. Bundle cost typically lands in the $11–$15/employee/month range depending on modules and headcount.

Lattice has shipped AI features in 2024–2026: AI-assisted review writing (drafts a review from feedback notes), summarization of survey verbatims, and "Lattice AI" insights surfacing engagement patterns. These are useful productivity features, especially the review-writing assist, but they''re table-stakes for the category now — 15Five and CultureAmp shipped equivalents in the same window.', 'https://lattice.com', 'subscription', '[{"plan":"Per-product (unbundled)","price":"$8/employee/month","features":["Choose Performance, Goals, or Engagement separately","1:1s, Feedback, and Updates included","Annual contract","$4,000/year minimum"]},{"plan":"Performance + Engagement bundle","price":"Custom (typically ~$11/employee/month)","features":["Performance reviews","Goals and OKRs","Engagement surveys","1:1s and feedback"]},{"plan":"Talent Suite","price":"Custom","features":["All Performance + Engagement features","Career growth frameworks","Compensation reviews","Advanced analytics"]},{"plan":"Enterprise","price":"Custom","features":["SSO/SAML","Custom review templates","API access","Dedicated CSM and SLA"]}]'::jsonb, 'beginner', true, '{"web","api","mobile"}', '{"Performance reviews (360, peer, manager, self)","Goals and OKRs with cascading","Continuous feedback (praise, constructive, requests)","1:1 agendas and notes","Engagement surveys with industry benchmarks","Career growth frameworks (ladders and competencies)","Compensation review cycles","Calibration tools for managers","AI-assisted review drafting and feedback summarization","Slack and Teams integrations for in-flow feedback","Reporting and analytics dashboards","Custom review templates"}', '{"Slack","Microsoft Teams","BambooHR","Workday","Rippling","ADP","Gusto","Greenhouse","Okta","Google Workspace","Salesforce"}', true, '{"100–2,000 person companies running structured performance cycles","People-ops teams that want goals + reviews + engagement on one platform","Companies tying performance to compensation in a defensible, calibrated way","Managers who run regular 1:1s and want a shared agenda tool"}', '{"Sub-50-person teams (overkill — a shared doc and Slack work fine)","Companies that want pure continuous coaching without formal cycles (15Five fits better)","Engagement-survey-only buyers (CultureAmp is deeper)","Enterprises >5,000 employees needing deep HCM integration (Workday is the safer bet)"}', 'The serious choice for performance management at 100–2,000 people. Pick Lattice if your Head of People wants to design custom review cycles and calibrate well; pick 15Five if continuous coaching is your bigger problem.', '{"https://help.lattice.com/"}', 'Pricing is sales-led and bundles can creep — the headline $8/employee/module rarely matches your final invoice once you stack Performance, Goals, and Engagement. Adoption is the real failure mode: Lattice only works if managers actually fill out 1:1s and feedback, and that''s a culture problem the software can''t fix. The engagement module is good but not best-in-class — CultureAmp goes deeper if surveys are your primary need. AI features are useful but not differentiated; every competitor has them now.', '{}', '{"reddit_threads":[]}'::jsonb, '{"Run a structured Q2 performance review cycle with 360 feedback for 300 employees in a defensible, calibrated way.","Cascade company OKRs to team and individual goals and track progress quarterly.","Run a quarterly engagement survey, slice results by team, and surface action items to managers.","Build a career-growth framework with competencies for engineers and let ICs see what the next level requires."}', 'Sweet spot: a 100–1,500 person company with a real Head of People who wants performance, goals, and engagement on one platform and is willing to invest in custom review-cycle design. Lattice rewards that investment — the calibration tooling, custom templates, and compensation-tie-in are genuinely better than what you can build in Google Docs or get from a free Notion template.

Failure modes. The single biggest one: deploying Lattice without manager-enablement. The platform shows you who isn''t doing 1:1s and who hasn''t given feedback in a quarter — but it doesn''t fix the underlying behavior, and unused Lattice is expensive shelfware. The second: bundle creep. Buyers start with Performance and end up with Performance + Goals + Engagement + Compensation + Grow over two years, often without re-evaluating whether each module earns its cost. The third: AI features as a buying reason — they''re fine, but the actual product is the cycle and feedback infrastructure underneath.

What to pilot. Run one performance cycle end-to-end (review templates, 360 invitations, calibration, manager training, results delivery) for one team. Measure manager adoption (% of expected 1:1 entries logged, % of feedback events given), time-to-complete reviews, and qualitative signal from employees. If managers actually use it in cycle 1, scale up. If not, the issue is enablement and Lattice can''t solve it for you — back off, train managers, then come back.', now()),
('BambooHR', 'bamboohr', 'HRIS purpose-built for small and mid-sized businesses — clean, simple, and battle-tested.', 'BambooHR is the most-used HRIS in the SMB segment in North America. The product covers the core HR workflow: employee records, onboarding/offboarding, time-off tracking, performance management (basic), reporting, e-signature for HR documents, and a self-service employee portal. Add-ons cover payroll (US only), benefits administration, time tracking, and applicant tracking. The whole thing is designed to be set up in days, not months — that''s the wedge against Workday and the reason BambooHR has dominated the 25–500 employee market for over a decade.

Direct competition: Gusto (which is payroll-first with HRIS bolted on, vs BambooHR''s HRIS-first with payroll bolted on), Rippling (more powerful, more expensive, more complex to deploy), Workday (enterprise-grade, overkill below 1,000 employees), Justworks (PEO-bundled, simpler but less flexible), and Paylocity (mid-market, deeper payroll). For a 25–500 employee US company that wants a real HRIS without enterprise weight, BambooHR is still the default choice in 2026.

Pricing tightened in 2025: Core is roughly $10/employee/month, Pro $17/employee/month, and Elite $25/employee/month, with a $250/month minimum for organizations under 25 employees. Pricing is custom-quoted, so real rates depend on company size, contract length, and add-ons (Payroll, Benefits Admin, Performance, Time Tracking are typically separate line items).

BambooHR has shipped AI features — AI-assisted job description writing, AI summaries on employee profiles, an AI search assistant inside the product — but these are productivity overlays, not a reason to buy. The reason to buy BambooHR is the same in 2026 as it was in 2018: a clean, well-designed, fast-to-deploy HRIS for SMBs.', 'https://bamboohr.com', 'subscription', '[{"plan":"Core","price":"~$10/employee/month (custom-quoted)","features":["Employee database and self-service","Hiring and onboarding","Time-off tracking","Basic AI-powered features","Reporting","Mobile app"]},{"plan":"Pro","price":"~$17/employee/month (custom-quoted)","features":["Everything in Core","Performance management","Employee community","Compliance training","Deeper culture and engagement tools"]},{"plan":"Elite","price":"~$25/employee/month (custom-quoted)","features":["Everything in Pro","Compensation management","Custom dashboards and analytics","HR benchmarking","300+ compliance training courses","Premium services"]},{"plan":"Add-ons","price":"Per-module","features":["Payroll (US only)","Benefits Administration","Time Tracking","Performance Management (Pro+)","Applicant Tracking System"]}]'::jsonb, 'beginner', true, '{"web","mobile","api"}', '{"Employee database and self-service portal","Onboarding and offboarding workflows","Time-off requests and tracking","Performance management (Pro+)","Applicant tracking system","E-signature for HR documents","US payroll (add-on)","Benefits administration (add-on)","Time tracking (add-on)","Compensation management (Elite)","Reporting and analytics","AI-assisted job descriptions and summaries","Mobile app for employees and managers","Compliance training library (Pro/Elite)"}', '{"Slack","Microsoft Teams","Google Workspace","Greenhouse","Lever","Indeed","Lattice","15Five","Deel","Rippling (data sync)","Okta","NetSuite","QuickBooks","Carta"}', true, '{"25–500 employee US-based companies","SMBs that want a clean HRIS without enterprise weight","Teams replacing spreadsheets, Google Drive, and DocuSign with one HR system","Companies that want US payroll and HRIS from one vendor"}', '{"Solo founders / sub-25 employee teams (the $250/month minimum hurts)","Heavily international companies (BambooHR is US-payroll-only — pair with Deel for global)","Enterprises >1,000 employees (Workday or Rippling will scale better)","Companies needing deep IT + Finance integration (Rippling fits better)"}', 'Still the best HRIS for a 25–500 employee US company that wants something clean, fast to deploy, and not enterprise-grade. The 2025 pricing tightening narrowed the gap with Rippling — re-evaluate at renewal.', '{"https://help.bamboohr.com/"}', 'US payroll only — international payroll requires a separate platform like Deel or Remote. Sub-25-employee minimum ($250/month) makes it expensive for very small teams. Reporting is solid but not as flexible as Rippling''s; advanced workflows often need an integration platform like Workato. Performance management module (in Pro/Elite) is functional but less powerful than dedicated tools like Lattice or 15Five. The AI features are real but thin — useful for boilerplate writing, not transformative. Pricing is sales-led and not published; expect quote variance.', '{}', '{"reddit_threads":[]}'::jsonb, '{"Onboard a new hire with offer letter, e-signature, benefits enrollment, and equipment checklist in one flow.","Track PTO and sick leave for 150 employees across multiple US states.","Run quarterly performance reviews using built-in templates without buying a separate Lattice subscription.","Generate compliance reports for SOC 2 audit (employee onboarding records, training completion, access removal at offboarding)."}', 'Sweet spot: a 50–300 employee US-only company that wants an HRIS to run for the next 5+ years without thinking about it. BambooHR is mature, well-supported, and doesn''t fight you. The Core tier is enough for most teams; Pro adds performance, which earns its keep if you don''t already have Lattice or 15Five.

Failure modes. Buyers stretch BambooHR past its sweet spot in two directions: scaling past 800–1,000 employees (where the reporting and workflow limits start to bite), and going international without pairing with Deel or Remote (where US-payroll-only becomes a real problem). The third common mistake: buying Pro or Elite for AI features that are nice but not load-bearing — Core is the right starting tier for most teams. Custom-quote pricing also means you should benchmark against published competitor list prices to make sure you''re getting a fair deal.

What to pilot. Run a 30-day trial with one full HR cycle: import employee data, run an onboarding for one new hire, process one PTO request, run one performance review, generate one report you actually need. If those flows feel obvious and fast, BambooHR will serve you well for years. If they feel clunky against your specific workflows, you''re probably looking at a Rippling or Workday-shaped problem that BambooHR was never designed to solve.', now()),
('Gusto', 'gusto', 'Modern payroll, benefits, and HR platform built for US small businesses.', 'Gusto runs payroll for over 300,000 US small businesses and is the de facto modern alternative to ADP and Paychex in the SMB market. The product''s core is full-service payroll: unlimited payroll runs, automated federal/state/local tax filing, W-2 and 1099 generation, multi-state support, and direct integration with major accounting tools. Around that core sit benefits administration (health, dental, vision, 401(k)), time tracking, hiring and onboarding, basic HR tools, and contractor payments.

The competitive set: ADP Run and Paychex Flex (legacy incumbents — wider feature set, dated UX, often more expensive once you negotiate), Rippling (more powerful, more complex, better fit at 50+ employees), Justworks (PEO model — bundles benefits at PEO-pool rates, less flexible), QuickBooks Payroll (cheaper but thinner), and OnPay (close competitor on price and quality). Gusto''s wedge is UX, support, and pricing transparency — pricing is published, the product feels modern, and the support team is widely reviewed as actually responsive. For a sub-50-employee US company, Gusto is the default 2026 recommendation.

Pricing as of March 2026: Simple at $49/month base + $6/employee/month, Plus at $80/month base + $12/employee/month, Premium at $180/month base + $22/employee/month. There''s also a Contractor-Only plan at $35/month + $6/contractor/month. The Simple plan got a 23% base-fee increase in March 2026 (from $40 to $49) — worth noting if you''re budgeting at renewal. State new-hire reporting, year-end W-2/1099 forms, and unlimited payroll runs are included on all paid plans.

Gusto has shipped AI features — Gusto AI (an in-app assistant for payroll/HR Q&A and tax-rule explanations) and AI-assisted onboarding workflows — but these are overlays, not the product. The reason to buy Gusto is the same as it''s been since 2014: best-in-class small-business payroll UX with honest pricing.', 'https://gusto.com', 'subscription', '[{"plan":"Simple","price":"$49/month base + $6/employee/month","features":["Full-service payroll (federal, state, local)","Unlimited payroll runs","W-2 and 1099 generation","Employee self-service","Health benefits administration","Basic hiring tools","Single-state filing"]},{"plan":"Plus","price":"$80/month base + $12/employee/month","features":["Everything in Simple","Multi-state payroll","Next-day direct deposit","Time tracking and PTO","Project tracking","Performance reviews","Team surveys"]},{"plan":"Premium","price":"$180/month base + $22/employee/month","features":["Everything in Plus","HR resource center and certified HR advisors","Compliance alerts","Dedicated support","Performance management","Full-service migration"]},{"plan":"Contractor Only","price":"$35/month + $6/contractor/month","features":["Unlimited contractor payments","1099 generation","Direct deposit","No W-2 employees"]}]'::jsonb, 'beginner', true, '{"web","mobile","api"}', '{"Full-service US payroll (federal, state, local taxes)","Unlimited payroll runs","Multi-state payroll (Plus+)","W-2 and 1099 generation","Direct deposit (next-day on Plus+)","Health, dental, vision, 401(k) benefits administration","Time tracking and PTO (Plus+)","Hiring and onboarding workflows","Contractor payments","Employee self-service portal","Compliance alerts (Premium)","HR advisors and resource center (Premium)","Gusto AI assistant for payroll/HR Q&A","Workers'' comp administration","Mobile app for employees"}', '{"QuickBooks","Xero","FreshBooks","Wave","Bench","Greenhouse","Lever","BambooHR","Lattice","15Five","Slack","Trainual","Homebase","When I Work","Deputy","Carta","Plaid"}', true, '{"US small businesses (1–50 employees)","Startups running their first payroll","Accountants serving multiple SMB clients","Companies with W-2 employees in 1–10 US states","Founders who want transparent, published pricing"}', '{"Companies with international employees (Gusto is US-only — pair with Deel for global)","Mid-market companies (50–500 employees) that need deeper HR + IT integration (Rippling fits better)","Enterprises with complex multi-entity structures","Companies needing a full-service PEO (Justworks or TriNet fit better)"}', 'The default US small-business payroll choice in 2026, even after the March price hike. UX, support, and pricing transparency still beat ADP/Paychex for sub-50-employee teams.', '{"https://support.gusto.com/"}', 'US-only — no international employees or contractors paid in foreign currencies. The March 2026 base-fee increase (Simple went from $40 to $49) narrowed Gusto''s price advantage; check OnPay and SurePayroll if cost is your top criterion. HR features outside payroll (performance, surveys) are functional but lighter than dedicated tools like Lattice. Tier gating is real — multi-state payroll requires Plus, dedicated support requires Premium, so very small teams can outgrow Simple faster than expected. The Gusto AI assistant is useful for payroll Q&A but not a transformative product feature.', '{}', '{"reddit_threads":[]}'::jsonb, '{"Run weekly payroll for 12 W-2 employees across 3 US states without thinking about tax filings.","Pay 25 contractors monthly with automatic 1099 generation at year-end.","Onboard a new hire with offer letter, I-9, W-4, direct deposit setup, and benefits enrollment in one flow.","Switch off ADP at year-end and migrate full payroll history to Gusto with their full-service migration."}', 'Sweet spot: a 1–50 employee US company that runs payroll regularly and wants to spend zero brain cycles on tax filings. Gusto is the right default — published pricing, modern UX, responsive support, and an integration list that covers most SMB stacks. The Simple plan is enough for most early-stage teams; upgrade to Plus when you cross into multi-state or want time tracking.

Failure modes. The biggest one: outgrowing Gusto silently. Past 50 employees, especially if you''re adding international hires or need deep IT/finance integration, Rippling or Deel start to fit better — but Gusto''s ease keeps you from re-evaluating. The second: getting tier-gated unexpectedly (multi-state payroll requires Plus, dedicated HR support requires Premium). The third: treating Gusto AI as a buying reason — it''s a useful Q&A overlay, but the actual product is the underlying payroll engine and the support team. Re-evaluate at renewal: the 2026 price hike is the kind of move worth pricing-checking against OnPay and SurePayroll.

What to pilot. Run one full payroll cycle (set up the company, add employees, run a real payroll, file taxes, deliver paystubs) on a 30-day trial. Time the setup, count support tickets you needed to open, and verify your specific state/locality filings are handled. If those three feel painless, Gusto will serve you well until you cross the mid-market threshold. If you hit friction in setup or filings, the issue is usually a complex multi-state or contractor situation that Gusto is honest about its limits on — pair with Deel for global, or move up-market to Rippling.', now()),
('Sunsama', 'sunsama', 'Mindful daily planner that time-boxes tasks and meetings into a sustainable workday.', 'Sunsama is a daily planning app for knowledge workers who want a calmer, more deliberate workflow than the usual to-do list pile. Each morning you "plan your day" — pulling tasks from Asana, Jira, Linear, Trello, Todoist, Gmail, Slack, Notion, or your calendar into a single ordered list, estimating how long each will take, and slotting them onto a time-blocked daily view. At the end of the day, a guided shutdown asks what got done, what got pushed, and what you learned.

Where Akiflow leans into being a maximalist productivity command center and Motion leans into AI-driven auto-scheduling, Sunsama is explicitly the opposite — slow, opinionated, deliberately constrained. The product makes you feel a small amount of friction when you over-commit, which is the point. Daily and weekly review rituals are first-class features rather than afterthoughts.

Integrations are deep on the read side: Sunsama pulls tasks bidirectionally from the major project trackers and email clients so you do not have to retype anything. The calendar view sits beside the task list, and dragging a task onto the calendar creates a real time-block synced to Google Calendar or Outlook. AI features are present but light — auto-planning suggestions, summary generation — not the centerpiece.

It is one of the most-loved tools among founders, executive coaches, and writers who treat focus as a scarce resource. The pricing is flat and premium, the team is small and product-focused, and the company has been quietly profitable for years.', 'https://sunsama.com', 'subscription', '[{"plan":"Pro Monthly","price":"$25/month","features":["Unlimited tasks and integrations","Daily and weekly planning rituals","Calendar time-blocking","AI auto-plan + MCP + Zapier","14-day free trial"]},{"plan":"Pro Annual","price":"$20/month billed yearly","features":["Same as Pro Monthly","20% annual discount","Priority support"]},{"plan":"Enterprise","price":"Custom","features":["SSO and SAML","SCIM and audit logs","Custom privacy and data terms","Dedicated CSM"]}]'::jsonb, 'beginner', false, '{"web","desktop","mobile"}', '{"Daily planning ritual with task pull-in","Time-boxed calendar view","Daily and weekly shutdown reviews","Two-way sync with Asana, Jira, Linear, Trello, Todoist","Email-to-task from Gmail and Outlook","Slack and Notion integrations","Focus mode with built-in timer","Keyboard-first UI","AI auto-plan suggestions","Recurring task templates"}', '{"Google Calendar","Outlook","Asana","Jira","Linear","Trello","Todoist","Gmail","Slack","Notion","Zapier","ClickUp","GitHub"}', true, '{"Founders, execs, and senior ICs who plan their day deliberately","Writers and researchers protecting deep-work blocks","Coaches and consultants running tight personal workflows","Anyone burnt out by infinite-list productivity apps"}', '{"Teams that need shared task assignment and project tracking","Users who want AI to auto-schedule everything for them (try Motion)","Power users who want a maximalist command center (try Akiflow)","Casual users who would not use a daily planning ritual"}', 'The most thoughtful daily planner on the market for people who treat focus as a scarce resource. Premium price, deliberately slow product, and the friction is the feature.', '{"https://help.sunsama.com/"}', 'Opinionated by design — if you do not want a daily planning ritual, the whole product feels heavy. The $20–25/month price is steep versus a basic to-do app. AI features are intentionally light; users wanting auto-scheduling will be disappointed. Integrations are read-heavy — full bidirectional sync varies by tool. No free tier beyond the 14-day trial.', '{}', '{"reddit_threads":[]}'::jsonb, '{"Run a 15-minute daily planning ritual that pulls tasks from Jira, Linear, and Gmail into one ordered day.","Time-block a deep-work morning and a meeting-heavy afternoon with explicit estimates per task.","End each day with a guided shutdown to log wins, blockers, and tomorrow''s top three.","Weekly review that surfaces what got pushed and what consistently overflows."}', 'Sweet spot: an executive, founder, or senior IC who already believes in time-blocking and just wants a clean tool that enforces the ritual without nagging. Sunsama gets out of your way once the morning plan is set, and the friction it adds at planning time pays back across the day.

Failure modes. The product is opinionated and slow on purpose. If you skip the daily planning ritual, Sunsama becomes an expensive task list. AI auto-scheduling is not the focus — power users who want Motion''s "AI runs my calendar" experience will find Sunsama frustrating. The integration depth is also lopsided: pulling tasks in is excellent, but pushing changes back out can lag for some tools, so do not treat it as a single source of truth for project state.

What to pilot. Use the 14-day trial during a normal work week, and actually do the morning plan + evening shutdown each day. If after two weeks you feel calmer and more in control of your day, the price pays for itself; if the ritual feels like overhead you skip, a free tool like Todoist plus Google Calendar will serve you better.', now()),
('Akiflow', 'akiflow', 'Task aggregator and time-blocker that funnels every inbox into a single keyboard-driven daily view.', 'Akiflow is a desktop-first productivity command center built around one core idea: every place tasks live — Gmail, Slack, Asana, Jira, Linear, ClickUp, Notion, Trello, Todoist, GitHub, Zoom — should funnel into a single unified inbox where you triage, schedule, and time-block them onto a real calendar. Where Sunsama is deliberately slow and ritual-based, Akiflow is maximalist, fast, and built for people who want raw throughput.

The keyboard shortcut layer is the giveaway: nearly every action has a hotkey, the command palette is a Cmd-K away, and power users can run their entire day without touching the mouse. The Aki AI assistant adds natural-language task creation, smart scheduling suggestions, and meeting prep from your calendar. Time-blocking is core — drag a task onto your Google or Outlook calendar and it becomes a real event you cannot easily miss.

Where Motion bets on AI to auto-schedule everything for you, Akiflow bets that humans want to feel in control while the tool removes friction. The integration list is deeper than Sunsama and broader than Motion — over 30 sources funnel into the unified inbox with two-way sync on most of them.

The product targets C-suite, busy professionals, and EAs who live in their calendar. Pricing reflects that — there is no free tier and the monthly cost is one of the highest in the category, which the company defends as evidence of who they are building for.', 'https://akiflow.com', 'subscription', '[{"plan":"Pro Monthly","price":"$34/month","features":["Unlimited integrations","Unlimited tasks and meetings","All power features","Aki AI executive assistant","7-day free trial"]},{"plan":"Pro Yearly","price":"$19/month billed annually","features":["44% annual discount","Same as Pro Monthly","1:1 onboarding call","Cancel anytime"]}]'::jsonb, 'intermediate', false, '{"desktop","web","mobile"}', '{"Unified inbox across 30+ tools","Keyboard-first command palette (Cmd-K)","Drag-to-calendar time-blocking","Two-way sync with Gmail, Slack, Asana, Jira, Linear","Aki AI assistant for scheduling and triage","Daily and weekly planner views","Recurring rituals and templates","Snooze and defer with smart defaults","Multi-calendar support (Google, Outlook, iCloud)","Meeting prep from calendar context"}', '{"Google Calendar","Outlook","iCloud Calendar","Gmail","Slack","Asana","Jira","Linear","ClickUp","Notion","Trello","Todoist","GitHub","Zoom","Microsoft Teams","Zapier","Salesforce"}', true, '{"C-level executives and founders","Power users with 5+ task and inbox sources","Executive assistants managing complex calendars","Consultants context-switching across many clients"}', '{"Casual users who only have one or two task sources","Users on a tight budget (no free tier)","People who dislike keyboard-shortcut UIs","Teams needing shared project management"}', 'The maximalist alternative to Sunsama. If you live in 5+ tools and want one keyboard-driven cockpit, Akiflow earns its premium. If you only have one inbox, the price is hard to justify.', '{"https://academy.akiflow.com/"}', 'UI complexity is the most-cited friction — first-week users often feel overwhelmed before the keyboard layer pays off. No free tier means you commit to the trial seriously or move on. Monthly pricing is among the highest in the category. Mobile app is functional but secondary to desktop. Some integrations (especially niche ones) sync more reliably than others.', '{}', '{"reddit_threads":[]}'::jsonb, '{"Funnel Slack mentions, Gmail stars, Jira tickets, and Asana tasks into one daily triage inbox.","Time-block your day with keyboard shortcuts and push events back to Google Calendar.","Use Aki AI to draft meeting prep notes from upcoming calendar context.","Run a weekly review across every connected tool without leaving Akiflow."}', 'Sweet spot: a senior professional or EA whose work spans many tools and who already thinks in keyboard shortcuts. Akiflow''s payoff curve is steep — the first three days are an investment, and around day five the throughput gain becomes obvious. People who genuinely have multiple task inboxes get real ROI; people with one inbox do not.

Failure modes. The breadth is the trap. New users try to wire up every integration on day one and end up with an unified inbox they can''t triage. Start with two sources, learn the shortcuts, and add more once the workflow feels stable. The other failure mode is treating Akiflow as a project-management replacement — it isn''t, and assignments still belong in Asana or Linear.

What to pilot. Take the 7-day trial seriously. Connect your two heaviest task sources, learn five keyboard shortcuts, and try to run a full day without leaving Akiflow. If the keyboard flow clicks, the annual plan is worth it; if it doesn''t, Sunsama or Todoist + Google Calendar will be cheaper and lighter.', now()),
('Vimcal', 'vimcal', 'Fast, keyboard-driven calendar app for executives and power users who live in their schedule.', 'Vimcal is a calendar app rebuilt from scratch for people who spend the majority of their day in calendar UI — founders, executives, executive assistants, investors, recruiters. The thesis is that Google Calendar and Outlook were designed when most professionals had two or three meetings a day, and that the modern reality of 8–15 meetings demands a faster, more keyboard-driven, more time-zone-aware tool.

Where Cron (now Notion Calendar) focused on a slick UI for individual contributors and Calendly focuses on external scheduling links, Vimcal sits squarely in the middle: it is your daily calendar client plus a personal scheduling layer. Every action — create event, find a slot, change time zone, send availabilities, copy holds — has a keyboard shortcut. The "drag-and-copy availabilities" feature lets you select free slots and paste them into an email as formatted text in seconds.

Vimcal EA, the higher tier, is built specifically for executive assistants managing calendars on behalf of principals. It adds 5-simultaneous-timezones view, calendar-audit reports, weekly calendar metrics, account handoff between EAs, and collaborative scheduling spreadsheets — workflows Google Calendar simply does not address.

The product is opinionated and premium-priced. The free tier is real but limited; the paid plans target users who already understand that a faster calendar is worth $20–75/month. Distribution is largely word-of-mouth in startup and venture circles.', 'https://vimcal.com', 'freemium', '[{"plan":"Free","price":"$0","features":["iOS Calendar","Drag and copy availabilities","Multi-time zone conversion","Duplicate event merging","Dark mode"]},{"plan":"Standard Monthly","price":"$20/month","features":["All free features","Unlimited personal booking links","Group scheduling polls","Desktop apps (Mac and PC)","Custom menu bar app"]},{"plan":"Standard Annual","price":"$16.67/month billed yearly","features":["33% annual discount","All Standard features"]},{"plan":"EA Scheduling","price":"$75/month or $62.50/month annual","features":["5 simultaneous time zones","Auto-created calendar holds","Collaborative scheduling spreadsheets","Calendar audits and weekly metrics","Customizable exec preferences","Account handoff","1:1 onboarding"]},{"plan":"Enterprise","price":"Custom","features":["Dedicated support manager","SAML SSO","Advanced security","Custom billing"]}]'::jsonb, 'intermediate', false, '{"web","desktop","mobile"}', '{"Keyboard-first event creation and editing","Drag-and-copy availabilities","Multi-timezone conversion (up to 5 simultaneous)","Personal booking links","Group scheduling polls","Auto-created EA holds","Calendar audit reports","Weekly calendar metrics","Account handoff between EAs","Conference link auto-injection (Zoom, Meet, Teams)","Native macOS, Windows, and iOS apps"}', '{"Google Calendar","Outlook","Zoom","Google Meet","Microsoft Teams","Slack","Loom","Around","HubSpot","Salesforce"}', true, '{"Founders and executives with 8+ meetings/day","Executive assistants managing principals'' calendars","Investors and recruiters running heavy scheduling loads","Anyone fighting time-zone confusion daily"}', '{"Casual users with 1–3 meetings/week (Google Calendar is fine)","Teams needing complex shared room booking","Users who want free unlimited scheduling (Cal.com is free)","Mobile-only users (desktop is the strength)"}', 'The fastest personal calendar in 2026 if you already love keyboard shortcuts and live in scheduling. The EA tier in particular is best-in-class — nothing else solves that workflow.', '{"https://docs.vimcal.com/"}', 'Pricing is premium versus free alternatives like Google Calendar and Cal.com — the value only shows up if you live in calendar UI. Mobile app trails the desktop experience. Integration list is solid for the major scheduling tools but lighter than Calendly for marketing-style booking flows. Enterprise features (provisioning, advanced compliance) only kick in at the custom tier.', '{}', '{"reddit_threads":[]}'::jsonb, '{"Run an executive''s 12-meeting day with keyboard-only navigation and one-key holds.","Send formatted availability blocks via email in 10 seconds rather than 3 minutes.","Manage a principal''s calendar across 5 time zones simultaneously without confusion.","Audit a calendar weekly to surface meeting load, focus blocks, and recurring time sinks."}', 'Sweet spot: someone whose job is meeting-heavy and who already wishes Google Calendar were faster. Vimcal''s gains compound across a day — saving 15 seconds per scheduling action across 30 actions a day adds up to real time recovered. The EA tier in particular has no real competition; if you''re scheduling for a busy principal, Vimcal pays for itself immediately.

Failure modes. People with light calendar load over-buy this — if you have 5 meetings a week, Vimcal is overkill and Google Calendar is free. The premium pricing is the most-cited objection, and it is only justified by saved minutes per day. Distribution outside startup-and-VC circles is still light, so external collaborators may have never seen a Vimcal booking link before.

What to pilot. Connect your primary work calendar, learn the 10 most useful shortcuts, and run a full week. If your daily calendar work feels measurably faster — fewer mis-clicks, faster availability sharing, less time-zone confusion — the cost is justified. If you barely notice the difference, your calendar load probably does not warrant a premium client.', now()),
('Read.ai', 'read-ai', 'Meeting analytics and AI summaries across Zoom, Google Meet, and Microsoft Teams.', 'Read.ai is an AI meeting copilot that joins Zoom, Google Meet, and Microsoft Teams calls to produce transcripts, summaries, action items, and analytics — sentiment, engagement, talk-time balance, pacing — that go beyond what Otter or Fireflies surface. Where Otter focuses on transcription quality and Fireflies focuses on CRM-style meeting workflows, Read.ai positions itself as the "meeting analytics" layer: the product wants to tell you not just what was said but how the meeting went and what to do differently next time.

The platform also includes Read AI Search, an enterprise search layer over your meetings, emails, and docs (with premium integrations to Notion, Salesforce, HubSpot, Jira, Confluence, and a Zapier/webhook surface). The Meeting Coach gives ongoing feedback on cadence, dominance, questions per minute, and other behavioral metrics — useful for sales coaching, executive presence, and team retros.

Integration depth at the paid tiers is where the differentiation lives. Pro adds premium integrations and 100 file upload credits/month for grounded answers. Enterprise adds audio/video playback and video highlights. Enterprise+ (10+ licenses) adds HIPAA, SSO, SAML, custom retention, and 8-hour meeting support — aimed at regulated industries and large orgs.

The free tier is real (5 transcripts/month, 1 hour max) and lets you evaluate quality before committing. The paid tiers compete head-to-head with Otter Business, Fireflies Pro, and Gong''s lighter SKUs.', 'https://read.ai', 'freemium', '[{"plan":"Free","price":"$0","features":["5 meeting transcripts/month","1-hour max meeting","Unlimited enterprise search","Summaries and transcription","Meeting coach","Basic integrations","20+ languages","Mobile and desktop apps"]},{"plan":"Pro","price":"$15/month annual or $19.75 monthly","features":["Unlimited transcripts","4-hour max meetings","Priority report processing","100 file upload credits/month","Premium integrations (Notion, Salesforce, HubSpot, Jira, Confluence, Zapier, webhooks)","LLM access"]},{"plan":"Enterprise","price":"$22.50/month annual or $29.75 monthly","features":["Unlimited transcripts","4-hour meetings","Audio and video playback","Video highlights","200 file upload credits/month","Premium support"]},{"plan":"Enterprise+","price":"$29.75/month annual or $39.75 monthly (10+ licenses)","features":["8-hour meeting support","HIPAA compliance","SSO and SAML","Domain capture","Custom data retention","300 file upload credits/month","Workspace onboarding"]}]'::jsonb, 'beginner', true, '{"web","desktop","mobile","api"}', '{"Auto-join Zoom, Meet, and Teams meetings","Live and post-meeting transcription (20+ languages)","AI summaries and action items","Sentiment and engagement analytics","Talk-time and pacing metrics","Meeting coach with behavioral feedback","Enterprise search over meetings, emails, and docs","Premium integrations (Notion, Salesforce, HubSpot, Jira, Confluence)","Webhooks and Zapier","Video highlights and playback (Enterprise+)","HIPAA + SSO + SAML (Enterprise+)"}', '{"Zoom","Google Meet","Microsoft Teams","Notion","Salesforce","HubSpot","Jira","Confluence","Zapier","Slack","Google Workspace","Microsoft 365"}', true, '{"Sales and CS teams running coachable meetings","Executives wanting analytics on their meeting load","Enterprises needing search across meetings and docs","Regulated industries needing HIPAA-grade compliance"}', '{"Privacy-conscious users who object to bots auto-joining","Teams already deeply on Otter or Fireflies (switching cost is real)","Solo users with <5 meetings/month (free tier is enough)","Highly technical conversations with heavy jargon (accuracy drops)"}', 'Read.ai differentiates on analytics and behavioral coaching, not just transcription. If you want a meeting copilot that scores meetings and surfaces patterns, it''s the strongest option; if you only need clean notes, Otter is cheaper and simpler.', '{"https://support.read.ai/"}', 'Transcription accuracy on heavy domain jargon (medical, legal, deep technical) lags Otter and dedicated speech vendors. The bot auto-joining behavior has caused friction with external participants who didn''t expect a third party in the room — orgs need a clear policy. Sentiment and engagement analytics are directional, not science — treat them as conversation starters, not performance reviews. Premium integrations are gated behind Pro+, so the free tier feels limited for power users.', '{}', '{"reddit_threads":[]}'::jsonb, '{"Auto-record and summarize a sales discovery call into a CRM-ready note pushed to HubSpot.","Coach a junior account exec by reviewing talk-time, question rate, and engagement metrics weekly.","Search across 6 months of meetings to find the moment a client agreed to a renewal term.","Run an enterprise-wide search over meetings + Notion + Confluence to answer policy questions."}', 'Sweet spot: a sales, customer success, or revenue org that already runs many video meetings and wants both clean notes and behavioral analytics. The coaching layer is genuinely useful for new-hire ramp, and the search layer makes meeting transcripts a real knowledge asset rather than dead text.

Failure modes. Two stand out. First, accuracy on jargon-heavy meetings is not perfect — finance, medicine, deep engineering will produce transcripts you must edit. Second, the bot showing up unannounced has caused real customer-relationship issues; orgs that adopt Read.ai need a "we record and summarize" disclosure baked into meeting invites. The analytics features can also be misused — engagement scores are not performance scores, and treating them as such produces bad management.

What to pilot. Use the free tier on 5 of your weekly recurring meetings for a month. Audit the transcripts for accuracy on your specific domain language. If the summaries and action items are usable with light editing, paid tiers are worth it; if you spend more time correcting than writing notes from scratch, a transcription-focused tool like Otter or a human note-taker will be more honest.', now()),
('SquadCast', 'squadcast', 'Remote podcast and video recording with studio-grade quality, now part of the Descript ecosystem.', 'SquadCast (acquired by Descript in 2023) is a browser-based remote recording studio for podcasters, video creators, and journalists who need broadcast-grade audio and video over the public internet. Unlike Zoom or Riverside-as-conferencing, SquadCast records each participant locally on their device, then uploads the full-quality file in the background — so the final recording is not limited by anyone''s bandwidth or call drops.

Where Riverside competes head-on with similar local-recording architecture, and Zencastr offers a similar feature set with a long-running indie reputation, SquadCast''s differentiation now lives in the Descript integration. Recordings flow directly into Descript''s editor — text-based audio editing, Studio Sound, transcript-driven cuts, multitrack stems — without the export-import friction that competitors require. For teams already using Descript, SquadCast removes a step from the production pipeline.

The product supports up to 10 mainstage participants on the Business tier (with separate audience/listener layers), 4K video on Creator+, video + screen recording, an AI suite (transcripts, show notes, clip suggestions, voice enhancement) measured in monthly minutes, and a stock library at the higher tiers. Recording hours are gated per tier, with the free tier giving 1 hour/editor/month for evaluation.

Pricing is per-editor with annual discounts up to 35%. The free tier is real but constrained; serious creators land on Hobbyist or Creator depending on how many shows and AI minutes they need.', 'https://squadcast.fm', 'freemium', '[{"plan":"Free","price":"$0","features":["1 recording hour/editor/month","1 show","10 participants","1 integration","Video and screen recording","Limited AI features"]},{"plan":"Hobbyist","price":"$16/month annual or $24 monthly","features":["10 recording hours/editor/month","5 shows","10 participants","2 integrations","Watermark-free 1080p exports","20 AI uses/month","30 minutes AI speech/month"]},{"plan":"Creator","price":"$24/month annual or $35 monthly","features":["30 recording hours/editor/month","Unlimited shows","Unlimited integrations","Unlimited AI suite","120 minutes AI speech/month","4K exports","Stock library access"]},{"plan":"Business","price":"$50/month annual or $65 monthly","features":["40 recording hours/editor/month","Unlimited shows","10 mainstage participants","Unlimited integrations","Full professional AI suite","300 minutes AI speech/month","Priority support with SLA"]}]'::jsonb, 'beginner', true, '{"web","desktop","mobile","api"}', '{"Local-first recording on each participant''s device","Studio-grade audio (up to 48 kHz WAV)","4K video recording (Creator and above)","Up to 10 mainstage participants","Video + screen recording","Direct Descript integration","AI transcripts, show notes, and clip suggestions","Voice enhancement","Stock library","Live audience and listener mode","Cloud backup with progressive upload"}', '{"Descript","Dropbox","Google Drive","Zapier","Riverside-compatible exports","Adobe Audition","Logic Pro","DaVinci Resolve"}', true, '{"Podcasters running multi-guest remote shows","Video creators needing broadcast-grade remote recording","Journalists conducting recorded remote interviews","Teams already using Descript for editing"}', '{"Live-streaming-first creators (use StreamYard)","Single-host solo recording (a local DAW is cheaper)","Teams committed to a non-Descript editing pipeline","Tight budgets — Riverside and Zencastr have similar free tiers"}', 'Best-in-class remote recording quality and the Descript integration is the moat. Pick it if Descript is already in your editing pipeline; otherwise Riverside is a coin-flip alternative.', '{"https://help.squadcast.fm/"}', 'Now tightly coupled to Descript — feature roadmap and pricing decisions flow through the parent company, which can cut both ways. Recording hours are metered per editor, so heavy production teams hit the cap quickly on Hobbyist and Creator. The 4K cap and full AI suite are gated behind Creator+, which raises the per-month commitment. Mobile experience is functional but desktop browser is the canonical surface. Live-streaming is not the focus.', '{}', '{"reddit_threads":[]}'::jsonb, '{"Record a 4-person remote podcast with each guest captured at full local quality.","Run a recorded remote video interview that flows straight into Descript for transcript-based editing.","Capture a multi-track stem of a remote panel show with separate audio per speaker.","Generate AI-powered show notes and clip suggestions immediately after recording wraps."}', 'Sweet spot: a podcaster or video creator who already lives in Descript for editing and wants a recording layer that hands off cleanly to the same tool. The local-first recording architecture genuinely solves the "guest dropped, the audio is gone" problem that plagued the Zoom-recording era of remote podcasting.

Failure modes. The Descript dependency is the single biggest one. If Descript''s strategic priorities shift, SquadCast''s roadmap shifts with them — and there have already been pricing and feature changes since acquisition that long-time users grumbled about. If you do not use Descript for editing, you''re paying a premium for a recording tool when Riverside or Zencastr cover the same need. Recording-hour metering also catches teams off guard — a daily show on Hobbyist''s 10 hours/editor cap is not enough.

What to pilot. Run two episodes on the free tier with a real guest and your full editing workflow. If the audio quality, the Descript hand-off, and the AI show-notes save you meaningful production time, the Creator tier pays for itself. If you''re happy with Zoom + a manual editing pass, SquadCast is a luxury rather than a need.', now()),
('Userpilot', 'userpilot', 'Product-led growth platform for in-app onboarding, engagement, and analytics — without code.', 'Userpilot is a no-code product-growth platform that lets PMs and lifecycle marketers build in-app onboarding flows, tooltips, checklists, NPS / CSAT surveys, resource centers, and event-driven campaigns without engineering tickets. You install one JavaScript snippet, point and click on UI elements to anchor experiences, segment by behavior or attributes, and ship — the entire authoring experience happens inside a Chrome extension overlaid on your live app.

Where Userpilot sits in the PLG-onboarding category: it is the more analytics-forward sibling of Appcues, the cheaper alternative to Pendo''s full Ultimate stack, and the more polished commercial counterpart to Userflow. Pendo is heavier and pricier with deeper enterprise governance; Appcues is the longest-running incumbent with a slick editor but thinner analytics; Userflow undercuts on price with a leaner, dev-friendlier product. Userpilot''s wedge is bundling product analytics + in-app guides + surveys + resource centers in a single subscription where competitors sell those as separate SKUs.

The 2025/2026 release cycle leaned hard into AI. Userpilot AI now drafts flow copy from a goal description, summarizes survey responses into themes, suggests segments based on funnel drop-offs, and generates onboarding checklists from a feature description. Session replay shipped as a paid add-on (formerly missing vs FullStory / Hotjar peers), and "AI Insights" now surfaces friction points across funnels without manually building reports.

Pricing is partly published, mostly sales-gated: Starter begins at $299/month for up to 2,000 MAUs and 3 seats; Growth and Enterprise are quote-based with MAU-scaled volume discounts and feature unlocks (event autocapture, session replay add-on, mobile, SSO, custom roles, data warehouse sync).', 'https://userpilot.com', 'subscription', '[{"plan":"Starter","price":"From $299/mo","features":["Up to 2,000 MAUs","3 seats","In-app engagement flows","User segmentation","NPS surveys","Usage trend analysis"]},{"plan":"Growth","price":"Custom","features":["From 5k MAUs","15 seats","Advanced product analytics","Event autocapture","Resource center","Email engagement","Session replay add-on","Mobile engagement add-on"]},{"plan":"Enterprise","price":"Custom","features":["Premium integrations","Bulk import/export","Data warehouse sync","SAML SSO","Custom roles","Activity logs","Security audit","Custom SLA"]}]'::jsonb, 'beginner', true, '{"web","api"}', '{"No-code in-app flow builder (Chrome extension)","Tooltips, modals, banners, hotspots, slideouts","Checklists and resource centers","NPS, CSAT, PMF surveys","Event autocapture and custom events","Funnel and trend analytics","User segmentation by behavior and attributes","Userpilot AI — flow copy, segment suggestions, survey summarization","Session replay (paid add-on)","Mobile in-app engagement (add-on)","Localization for multi-language flows","A/B testing on flows","Webhook and SDK integrations"}', '{"Segment","HubSpot","Salesforce","Mixpanel","Amplitude","Heap","Intercom","Slack","Zapier","Google Analytics","Snowflake","BigQuery","Redshift","Webhook"}', true, '{"PMs and PMMs running onboarding without engineering tickets","Lifecycle and growth marketers in PLG SaaS","Customer success teams driving feature adoption","Mid-market B2B SaaS replacing Appcues + Pendo + survey tools with one stack"}', '{"Pre-product startups with no live users to engage","Mobile-first apps where in-app coverage matters more than web (mobile is an add-on, not core)","Enterprises with strict on-prem requirements (cloud-only)","Teams that need deep funnel analytics rivaling Mixpanel / Amplitude as their primary analytics tool"}', 'The most balanced PLG-onboarding platform in 2026 — pick it if you want guides + analytics + surveys in one subscription without paying Pendo Ultimate prices. Skip it if mobile is your primary surface or if Appcues'' editor polish matters more to you than analytics depth.', '{"https://docs.userpilot.com/"}', 'Pricing is opaque past Starter — Growth tier negotiation can swing several thousand dollars depending on MAU band and add-ons. Session replay is a paid add-on, not core, so the all-in cost vs FullStory parity is real. Mobile in-app engagement is a separate add-on with thinner feature parity than the web product. Heavy SPA frameworks (Next.js App Router with aggressive prefetching, dynamic routes) occasionally need engineering glue to anchor flows reliably. AI features are useful but shallow vs purpose-built copy tools — treat them as drafting aids, not finished output.', '{}', '{"reddit_threads":[]}'::jsonb, '{"Ship a multi-step onboarding checklist for new signups in a B2B SaaS without filing engineering tickets.","Run a feature-adoption campaign with in-app banners, segmented to users who haven''t tried the new feature within 14 days.","Trigger NPS surveys after a key activation event and route detractors to a CS workflow via Slack.","Replace Appcues + a separate analytics tool + a separate survey tool with one Userpilot subscription.","Build a resource center inside your app so users get help docs without leaving the product."}', 'Sweet spot: a 20–200-person B2B SaaS where the PM / PMM team owns onboarding and adoption, the engineering team is tired of getting pulled into "can you ship this tooltip" tickets, and the analytics needs are real but not Mixpanel-deep. Userpilot collapses three SaaS subscriptions (guides + surveys + product analytics-lite) into one and gets non-engineers shipping in-app experiences in a week.

Failure modes to know. Mid-market teams underestimate the Growth-tier price jump — Starter''s $299 looks great until you cross 2k MAUs and the next quote arrives. Mobile parity is a known gap; if mobile in-app engagement is the core need, evaluate Pendo or a mobile-first specialist before signing. SPA frameworks with aggressive client-side routing sometimes break flow anchoring — pilot on your real production app, not the marketing site. Userpilot AI ships drafts, not finished copy; reviewing every AI-generated string is non-negotiable.

What to pilot before committing. Run a 30-day trial. Build three real flows (an onboarding checklist, a feature announcement, an NPS survey), instrument the activation event you actually care about, and measure whether non-engineers can ship without help. If your PM ships all three solo and the analytics surface the right segments, the renewal math works; if engineering keeps getting pulled in for selector fixes or event plumbing, the savings vs a hand-rolled solution evaporate quickly.', now()),
('Pendo', 'pendo', 'Enterprise product-experience platform — analytics, in-app guides, session replay, and AI insights.', 'Pendo is the category-defining product-experience platform: a single stack for product analytics, in-app guides and onboarding, session replay, NPS / PMF / CSAT surveys, and roadmap planning. Install the Pendo agent once and it autocaptures every click, page view, and feature interaction without engineering instrumentation — the central trade-off Pendo makes vs Mixpanel / Amplitude / Heap, which require explicit event taxonomy work but reward you with cleaner long-term data models.

Where Pendo sits in the product-analytics category: Mixpanel and Amplitude are deeper on event-based analytics and warehouse-native modeling but ship no in-app guides; Heap matches Pendo on autocapture but historically lacked the guides surface (now closing that gap). Pendo''s differentiator is the bundle — analytics + guides + replay + surveys + Listen (voice-of-customer) + Orchestrate (cross-channel campaigns) under one Ultimate-tier contract — plus the deepest enterprise governance in the category (SOC 2, HIPAA-ready tiers, EU data residency, fine-grained RBAC, audit logs, SAML / SCIM).

The 2025/2026 AI push is substantial. Pendo Listen (acquired Mind the Product''s research function and re-released as an AI feature) clusters open-ended feedback into themes automatically. Predict AI scores users by churn / expansion likelihood from product-usage patterns. Agent Analytics (announced 2025) instruments AI agent products specifically — tracking tool use, hallucination rates, and agent-vs-user task completion. Pendo AI also generates in-app guide copy from a goal prompt and summarizes session replays into highlight reels.

Pricing is mostly sales-gated. A genuine free tier covers up to 500 MAUs with product analytics, in-app guides, and Pendo-branded NPS — useful for early-stage validation. Paid tiers (Base, Core, Ultimate) are quote-based with MAU-scaled volume discounts; Ultimate adds session replay, full sentiment surveys, Orchestrate, Listen, and Data Sync. Predict AI and Agent Analytics are priced as separate add-on modules.', 'https://pendo.io', 'freemium', '[{"plan":"Free","price":"$0","features":["Up to 500 MAUs","Product analytics","In-app guides","Pendo-branded NPS"]},{"plan":"Base","price":"Custom","features":["Custom MAU volume","Product analytics","In-app guides"]},{"plan":"Core","price":"Custom","features":["Everything in Base","Session replay"]},{"plan":"Ultimate","price":"Custom","features":["Everything in Core","Full sentiment surveys (NPS, PMF, CSAT)","Orchestrate","Listen","Data Sync"]},{"plan":"Add-ons","price":"Custom","features":["Predict AI","Agent Analytics"]}]'::jsonb, 'intermediate', true, '{"web","mobile","api"}', '{"Autocapture product analytics (clicks, pages, features)","In-app guides — tooltips, walkthroughs, lightboxes","Session replay (Core+ tier)","NPS, PMF, CSAT sentiment surveys","Pendo Listen — AI clustering of open-ended feedback","Predict AI — churn and expansion scoring","Agent Analytics — instrumentation for AI agent products","Pendo AI — guide copy generation and replay summarization","Roadmap planning (Pendo Roadmaps)","Orchestrate — cross-channel campaigns (in-app + email)","Data Sync — warehouse export to Snowflake / BigQuery / Redshift","Mobile SDK (iOS, Android, React Native)","SSO, SAML, SCIM, audit logs","HIPAA-ready and EU data residency tiers"}', '{"Salesforce","HubSpot","Segment","Snowflake","BigQuery","Redshift","Slack","Jira","Zendesk","Intercom","Okta","Azure AD","Google Analytics"}', true, '{"Mid-market and enterprise B2B SaaS standardizing on one product-experience stack","Product orgs that want analytics + guides + surveys without juggling three vendors","Regulated industries (healthcare, finance) needing HIPAA / EU residency","Teams instrumenting AI agent products with Agent Analytics"}', '{"Early-stage startups (paid tiers price out fast — start with Free or Mixpanel)","Engineering-heavy orgs that want a strict event taxonomy (Mixpanel / Amplitude reward that discipline more)","Teams who only need session replay (FullStory / Hotjar are cheaper for that single use case)","Pure mobile-first apps where Pendo''s mobile coverage lags the web product"}', 'The default enterprise product-experience platform in 2026 — the bundle is genuinely best-in-class and the governance story is unmatched. The cost is real, and the autocapture model is a long-term commitment that''s hard to migrate off.', '{"https://help.pendo.io/"}', 'Pricing is fully sales-gated past the 500 MAU free tier — expect five-figure annual contracts at the Core tier and six-figure at Ultimate for mid-market scale. Autocapture is convenient on day one but locks you into Pendo''s data model — migrating to Mixpanel / Amplitude later requires re-instrumenting from scratch. Mobile SDK feature parity lags the web product, especially around session replay and Orchestrate. AI features (Listen, Predict, Pendo AI) are useful but thinner than purpose-built tools — Listen''s clustering is decent but not Reveal-level qualitative depth. SPA framework support is solid but not perfect; complex client-side routing can confuse autocapture and require manual page-tagging.', '{}', '{"reddit_threads":[]}'::jsonb, '{"Instrument a B2B SaaS with one Pendo agent and get autocaptured analytics, in-app guides, surveys, and replay without engineering tickets.","Cluster six months of open-ended feedback into themes with Pendo Listen and feed the top three into the next quarterly roadmap.","Score every account by churn likelihood with Predict AI and route at-risk accounts to CS via Salesforce.","Instrument an AI agent product with Agent Analytics to track tool-use success, hallucination rates, and user-vs-agent task completion.","Run a HIPAA-compliant in-app onboarding flow inside a regulated healthtech product."}', 'Sweet spot: a mid-market or enterprise B2B SaaS at 5,000+ MAUs where product, CS, and lifecycle teams all need access to the same product-usage truth, and the org has decided buying one bundle beats integrating Mixpanel + Appcues + Hotjar + a survey tool. Pendo''s governance, mobile SDK, and warehouse-sync pricing premium are justified at that scale; below it, the math is brutal.

Failure modes to know. The two most common Pendo regrets: (1) buying it too early — pre-product-market-fit teams get locked into a six-figure contract for features they don''t use yet, and (2) treating autocapture as a substitute for event taxonomy — three years in, your data model is whatever Pendo decided to capture, and migrating to a warehouse-native analytics tool costs months. The AI features are real but not differentiating against Reveal / Dovetail (research) or Mixpanel (predictive) on their respective home turfs. SPA-heavy apps need engineering involvement during setup despite the "no code" pitch.

What to pilot before signing. Run the free tier for 60 days against a real product with at least 200 MAUs. Build three flows, ship one survey, validate that autocapture correctly identifies your key features (it often misnames things on dynamic UIs). Then negotiate the paid tier knowing your actual MAU trajectory and which add-ons you''ll genuinely use — Ultimate without Listen / Predict / Orchestrate adoption is overpriced; Ultimate with all three deeply integrated into workflow is best-in-class.', now()),
('Userflow', 'userflow', 'Developer-friendly user onboarding and product tours — built by engineers, priced for startups.', 'Userflow is a no-code in-app onboarding platform built explicitly as a leaner, dev-friendlier alternative to Userpilot, Appcues, and Pendo. The flow builder runs as a Chrome extension over your live app, the snippet is a single line, and the API surface is the most polished in the category — events, identify calls, and flow triggering all behave the way an engineer expects. Customers consistently cite "felt like it was built by someone who''s shipped product" as the reason they pick it.

Where Userflow sits in the PLG onboarding category: cheaper than Userpilot at the entry tier ($240/month for 3,000 MAUs vs $299/month for 2,000), more analytics-light than Pendo (no session replay, no autocapture), and more developer-respecting than Appcues (cleaner API, no XPath-fragile selectors). The trade-off: Userflow does one thing — onboarding flows + checklists + tours + surveys — and does it well, but you''ll pair it with a separate product-analytics tool (Mixpanel, Amplitude, PostHog) rather than getting an all-in-one.

The AI feature set shipped in 2025 is deliberately scoped: AI flow generation drafts a multi-step onboarding sequence from a feature description; AI translation localizes existing flows into 30+ languages with one click; AI survey insights summarize open-ended responses into themes. Userflow has resisted bolting on session replay and product analytics, choosing instead to integrate cleanly with the analytics tools customers already use.

Pricing is published and unusually transparent for the category. Startup is $240/month annually ($300 monthly) for 3,000 MAUs and 3 seats; Pro is $680/month annually ($850 monthly) for 10,000 MAUs and unlimited team members; Enterprise is custom with SSO, security audits, concierge support, and a CSM. Extra MAU bundles are $80/month per 5,000 (annual) and additional seats are $16/month each.', 'https://userflow.com', 'subscription', '[{"plan":"Startup","price":"From $240/mo (annual)","features":["Up to 3,000 MAUs","3 seats","All flow types","NPS / surveys","Checklists","Resource center","API access"]},{"plan":"Pro","price":"$680/mo (annual)","features":["Up to 10,000 MAUs","Unlimited team members","2 extra environments (staging, testing)","Localization","Advanced targeting","Priority support"]},{"plan":"Enterprise","price":"Custom","features":["Custom MAU volume","SSO / SAML","Security audits","Concierge support","Dedicated CSM","Removed feature caps"]},{"plan":"Add-ons","price":"From $80/mo per 5,000 MAUs","features":["Extra MAU bundles","Extra seats $16/mo each (annual)"]}]'::jsonb, 'beginner', true, '{"web","api"}', '{"No-code flow builder (Chrome extension)","Tooltips, modals, banners, hotspots, checklists","Resource center with help docs","NPS, CSAT, PMF surveys","AI flow generation from feature description","AI translation into 30+ languages","AI survey insights — theme clustering","Clean REST API for events, identify, flow triggering","Staging and testing environments (Pro)","Localization for multi-language flows","Segmentation by user attributes and events","SSO / SAML (Enterprise)","Theme builder for design system match"}', '{"Segment","Mixpanel","Amplitude","Heap","PostHog","HubSpot","Intercom","Slack","Zapier","Webhook","Google Analytics"}', true, '{"PLG startups and 10–100-person SaaS teams","Engineering-heavy orgs that want a clean API surface","Teams already using Mixpanel / Amplitude who want onboarding without rebuying analytics","Cost-conscious mid-market teams switching off Userpilot or Appcues"}', '{"Mobile-first apps (Userflow is web-only — no native mobile SDK)","Teams who need session replay, product analytics, or autocapture in the same tool","Pure no-code shops that prefer Appcues'' more visual editor","Enterprises that want one vendor for analytics + guides + replay (Pendo fits better)"}', 'The right choice for engineering-led PLG teams who want a clean, well-priced onboarding tool and already have an analytics stack. Skip it if you need mobile, session replay, or want one bundle for everything.', '{"https://userflow.com/docs/"}', 'Web-only — no native mobile SDK. No session replay or product analytics built in (intentional, but means you''re paying two vendors). The Chrome-extension authoring experience is great for desktop but weaker on responsive / mobile-web layouts. AI features ship as drafting aids, not finished output — review every generated string. SPA frameworks with aggressive route-level code splitting occasionally need manual page-tag config. Pricing is published and fair, but additional MAU bundles past Pro can add up at scale — model the ramp before committing annually.', '{}', '{"reddit_threads":[]}'::jsonb, '{"Ship a SaaS onboarding checklist with three guided tours in a week, paired with Mixpanel or PostHog for analytics.","Localize an entire onboarding flow into eight languages with AI translation in one afternoon.","Trigger flows from your own backend using Userflow''s event API after a webhook fires from Stripe.","Replace a Userpilot subscription at half the price after auditing actual feature usage.","Build a resource center inside a B2B SaaS so customers get help without leaving the app."}', 'Sweet spot: a 10–100-person PLG SaaS team where engineering values a clean API and product values not paying for features they won''t use. Userflow''s pricing transparency, dev-respecting integration, and tightly-scoped feature set make it the path of least resistance for teams who already have a separate analytics tool. The Pro tier ($680/month for 10k MAUs, unlimited seats) is one of the best deals in the PLG-onboarding category if you don''t need mobile or replay.

Failure modes to know. Teams who pick Userflow expecting a Pendo-level bundle hit the limits fast — there is no session replay, no autocapture, and mobile is not on the roadmap as of early 2026. The "build by engineers, for engineers" positioning means non-technical PMs sometimes find the Chrome-extension authoring experience less guided than Appcues''. AI flow generation is a useful starting point but the output reads generic without heavy editing. SPA-heavy frameworks (Next.js App Router, Remix with streaming) occasionally need extra page-tag configuration despite the "one snippet" pitch.

What to pilot before signing. Build one real onboarding flow on the Startup tier in a 14-day trial. Wire the events into your existing analytics tool. Have a non-technical PM author one tour solo. If the PM ships without engineering help and the analytics integration cleanly shows flow-driven activation lift, the value is obvious; if either step requires engineering escalation or the analytics integration feels brittle, evaluate Userpilot or Pendo (more bundled) or Appcues (more visual) before committing annually.', now()),
('FullStory', 'fullstory', 'Enterprise digital-experience analytics — session replay, autocaptured product analytics, and AI insights.', 'FullStory is the enterprise leader in digital-experience analytics: pixel-perfect session replay, autocaptured product analytics, heatmaps, funnels, error tracking, and StoryAI for natural-language exploration of user behavior. The technical bet that defined the category — capture every DOM mutation server-side rather than relying on JavaScript-side instrumentation — produces replay quality and search depth that Hotjar and LogRocket genuinely cannot match at scale.

Where FullStory sits in the session-replay category: Hotjar is the cheaper, marketing-friendly tool for SMBs that want heatmaps + recordings without the analytics depth; LogRocket is the developer-focused alternative emphasizing error tracking, console logs, and Redux state replay (the right pick if engineering owns it primarily). FullStory''s wedge is the combination — replay that actually replays everything, plus product analytics deep enough to compete with Mixpanel / Amplitude on funnels and segmentation, plus enterprise governance (SOC 2, HIPAA, fine-grained data privacy, EU residency).

The 2025/2026 AI release was substantial. StoryAI lets product / CX / support teams ask natural-language questions ("show me sessions where users abandoned the cart after a 500 error") and get filtered replays without building queries. AI-powered recommendations surface friction patterns proactively across funnels. Frustration signals (rage clicks, dead clicks, error clicks) are auto-classified with AI confidence scores. Mobile coverage shipped real improvements in 2025 — iOS / Android SDKs now capture native session replay with redaction controls — closing a long-standing gap vs the web product.

Pricing is fully sales-gated. The free tier (FullstoryFree) is genuinely useful: 30,000 sessions/month with 12 months retention. Paid tiers — Business, Advanced, Enterprise — scale by session volume, retention, and feature unlock. Annual contracts run roughly $10k–$25k for entry-level Business deployments (50k–100k sessions/month), $30k–$70k for mid-market Advanced, and $80k–$200k+ for Enterprise with mobile and full add-ons.', 'https://fullstory.com', 'freemium', '[{"plan":"FullstoryFree","price":"$0","features":["30,000 sessions/month","12 months retention","Session replay","Basic search"]},{"plan":"Business","price":"Custom (~$10k–$25k/yr)","features":["Session replay","Heatmaps","Basic search and segmentation","Standard retention"]},{"plan":"Advanced","price":"Custom (~$30k–$70k/yr)","features":["Everything in Business","Dashboards","Funnels","User trends","Retention analysis","Advanced segmentation"]},{"plan":"Enterprise","price":"Custom (~$80k–$200k+/yr)","features":["Everything in Advanced","Data Studio","AI-powered recommendations","Advanced data management","Custom retention","Premium SLA"]},{"plan":"Add-ons","price":"Custom","features":["Mobile analytics","StoryAI","Multi-Org Management","Guides and Surveys","Anywhere (Warehouse + Activation)"]}]'::jsonb, 'intermediate', true, '{"web","mobile","api"}', '{"Pixel-perfect session replay (web and mobile)","Autocapture product analytics","Heatmaps (click, scroll, attention)","Funnels and conversion analysis","Frustration signals (rage / dead / error clicks)","StoryAI — natural-language session search","AI-powered friction recommendations","Error tracking and console capture","User segmentation and trend analysis","Mobile SDKs (iOS, Android, React Native)","Data privacy controls — element-level redaction","SOC 2, HIPAA-ready, EU data residency","Warehouse export (FullStory Anywhere)","Guides and Surveys add-on","Webhook and SDK extensibility"}', '{"Segment","Salesforce","HubSpot","Slack","Jira","Zendesk","Intercom","Snowflake","BigQuery","Redshift","Mixpanel","Amplitude","Google Analytics","Okta","Azure AD"}', true, '{"Mid-market and enterprise digital products needing replay + analytics in one stack","E-commerce and SaaS teams diagnosing conversion friction","CX and support teams investigating user-reported issues with replay context","Regulated industries needing HIPAA / EU residency for replay data","Mobile-first apps now that mobile SDKs reached parity"}', '{"Early-stage startups (the free tier is great, but paid jumps to $10k+/yr)","Teams who only need heatmaps (Hotjar is dramatically cheaper)","Engineering-led error-tracking-first use cases (LogRocket fits better)","Cost-sensitive SMBs who can''t justify five-figure annual contracts"}', 'The default enterprise digital-experience platform in 2026 — replay quality and StoryAI are genuinely category-leading. The free tier is unusually generous, but paid tier pricing is steep and fully sales-gated.', '{"https://help.fullstory.com/"}', 'Pricing is fully opaque past the free tier — expect a sales cycle to get any quote, and contracts vary widely based on session volume and add-on selection. Storage and bandwidth costs of full-fidelity replay mean session retention is a real cost lever — don''t over-buy retention. Mobile parity arrived in 2025 but is still newer than the web product; pilot mobile coverage on your real app before assuming feature parity. StoryAI is impressive for natural-language exploration but occasionally surfaces irrelevant sessions on ambiguous queries — treat it as a search aid, not an analyst replacement. Privacy-sensitive industries need careful redaction config — defaults are not aggressive enough for healthcare / finance use cases out of the box.', '{}', '{"reddit_threads":[]}'::jsonb, '{"Diagnose a 30% checkout-conversion drop by replaying every session that abandoned at the payment step.","Ask StoryAI in natural language: ''show me sessions where users hit a 500 error then immediately churned.''","Surface rage-click clusters across an e-commerce site and feed them into the next sprint.","Investigate a customer-reported bug by jumping directly to that user''s exact session from a Zendesk ticket.","Run a HIPAA-compliant session-replay deployment inside a regulated healthtech product."}', 'Sweet spot: a mid-market or enterprise B2C / B2B product where replay-driven friction analysis genuinely changes conversion or support outcomes, and the org can absorb a five-figure annual contract. FullStory''s replay quality, StoryAI, and enterprise governance make it the obvious pick at that scale — Hotjar is meaningfully thinner and LogRocket is a different category. The free tier is also legitimately useful for early-stage teams to validate fit before signing paid.

Failure modes to know. The most common FullStory regret is over-buying — teams sign Enterprise with mobile + StoryAI + Anywhere expecting to use everything, then discover six months in that 80% of usage is replay + funnels and the bundle was overpriced. Storage cost on full-fidelity replay also surprises teams; retention is a legitimate cost lever to negotiate down. SPA-heavy frameworks (Next.js with streaming, Remix) occasionally need engineering tuning to capture replay correctly on dynamic routes. StoryAI is genuinely useful but produces uneven results on ambiguous queries — pilot it against questions you actually ask, not demo prompts.

What to pilot before signing. Run the FullstoryFree tier for 60 days against a real production surface. Build three funnels, run StoryAI against five real product questions, validate that mobile SDK coverage works on your stack. Negotiate the paid tier knowing your actual session volume, what retention you genuinely need (not what they recommend), and which add-ons you''ll use. Mobile, StoryAI, and Anywhere are commonly over-bought — pay for them only if pilot data justifies it.', now()),
('Maze', 'maze', 'AI-powered user research and usability testing — unmoderated, moderated, and AI-moderated studies.', 'Maze is a continuous user-research platform that runs unmoderated usability tests, prototype tests, surveys, card sorts, tree tests, and (newer) AI-moderated interviews — all from one workspace. The core promise: research that used to take a UX agency two weeks and a five-figure budget now runs in two days from a self-serve tool, with AI handling synthesis. It pairs especially well with Figma, where Maze imports prototypes natively and tests them against real users.

Where Maze sits in the UX-research category: UserTesting is the incumbent enterprise platform with the deepest panel network and the highest cost — it owns moderated video research at scale. Lookback is the moderated-interview specialist with the best live-session UX. Maze is the unmoderated + AI-moderated leader, undercutting UserTesting on price and beating Lookback on automated test types. The platform''s methodology bias is toward fast, frequent, lightweight studies rather than the deep, expensive moderated sessions UserTesting champions.

The 2025/2026 AI release defined the product''s second act. Maze AI synthesizes test results into themes and recommended actions automatically, replacing a research-ops bottleneck that historically took designers half a day per study. AI Moderator (launched 2024, matured 2025) runs unmoderated interviews where an AI asks follow-up questions in real time based on participant answers — bridging the gap between "cheap unmoderated test" and "expensive moderated interview." Automated reports generate readouts in the Maze format with one click. The AI panel-recruitment improvements help match participants to study criteria more accurately.

Pricing has Free, Starter, Organization, and Enterprise tiers. Free covers basic prototype testing with 10 testers/month and one user — useful for solo designers validating fit. Starter is $99/month annual ($1,188/year) with 100 testers/month and core features. Organization is custom-priced for larger teams (typical Vendr median around $12k/year for mid-market). Enterprise unlocks AI Moderator, mobile testing, interview studies, panel recruitment at volume, and the full security/compliance stack.', 'https://maze.co', 'freemium', '[{"plan":"Free","price":"$0","features":["1 user","10 testers/month","Prototype testing","Maze AI (limited)","Basic features"]},{"plan":"Starter","price":"$99/mo (annual, $1,188/yr)","features":["100 testers/month","All core test types","Prototype + survey + card sort + tree test","Maze AI","50% student discount available"]},{"plan":"Organization","price":"Custom (~$12k/yr median)","features":["500+ testers/month","Advanced collaboration","Panel recruitment","Advanced reporting","Priority support"]},{"plan":"Enterprise","price":"Custom","features":["AI Moderator","Mobile testing","Interview studies","Volume panel recruitment","SSO / SAML","Security and compliance stack","Dedicated CSM"]}]'::jsonb, 'beginner', true, '{"web","api"}', '{"Unmoderated prototype testing","AI Moderator — AI-led unmoderated interviews","Maze AI — automated synthesis and theme clustering","Surveys (in-product and standalone)","Card sorting (open and closed)","Tree testing","First-click testing","Five-second testing","Mobile usability testing (Enterprise)","Interview studies (Enterprise)","Native Figma integration","Panel recruitment with AI matching","Automated reports","Heatmaps and click maps","Conditional logic and branching","SSO / SAML (Enterprise)"}', '{"Figma","Adobe XD","Sketch","Maze panel","Slack","Notion","Jira","Zapier","Webhook","Google Analytics","Mixpanel"}', true, '{"Product designers and UX researchers running continuous research","Mid-market product teams replacing periodic UX-agency engagements","Startups validating prototypes before engineering investment","Research-ops teams scaling unmoderated + AI-moderated studies"}', '{"Teams that primarily need deep moderated video research at scale (UserTesting fits better)","Pure live-interview workflows (Lookback is more focused)","Enterprises with strict on-prem requirements (cloud-only)","Researchers who distrust AI synthesis and want manual coding (Dovetail / Reduct fit better)"}', 'The right choice for design and product teams that want continuous, fast, AI-synthesized research without UserTesting''s price tag. AI Moderator is genuinely novel — bridging unmoderated cost with moderated depth.', '{"https://help.maze.co/"}', 'AI Moderator, mobile testing, and interview studies are gated to Enterprise — Starter and Organization users hit those limits frequently. Maze AI synthesis is fast but produces generic themes on ambiguous data; treat it as a starting draft, not a finished research report. Panel recruitment is solid for common personas (B2C consumer, general product users) but thinner for niche / B2B / regulated audiences vs UserTesting''s curated panel. Mobile testing arrived later than the web product and still feels secondary in the UI. AI features genuinely save time but should never replace researcher judgment on study design — the bottleneck shifts from synthesis to study quality.', '{}', '{"reddit_threads":[]}'::jsonb, '{"Run a five-second test on three landing-page variants and ship the winner inside a week.","Test a Figma prototype with 50 real users in two days, with Maze AI clustering responses into themes.","Run an AI-moderated interview series where the AI asks follow-up questions based on participant answers.","Validate an information architecture with a tree test before committing engineering to the navigation.","Replace a quarterly UX-agency engagement with continuous in-house research at a fraction of the cost."}', 'Sweet spot: a 10–100-person product team where design and research want to ship fast, frequent studies and the org has decided continuous research beats periodic agency engagements. Maze''s pricing, AI synthesis, and Figma integration make it the path of least resistance for that workflow. AI Moderator is the genuinely new capability — if you''ve historically run unmoderated tests because moderated felt too expensive, AI Moderator may legitimately change what research is feasible.

Failure modes to know. Teams who treat Maze AI synthesis as finished research output produce shallow insights — the AI clusters themes well but doesn''t replace researcher judgment on study design or interpretation. Panel-recruitment quality is real but variable for niche audiences; budget for your own recruiting if you need B2B specialists or regulated-industry participants. The Starter-to-Enterprise feature gap is large (no AI Moderator, no mobile, no interviews on Starter), so growing teams hit a pricing cliff that requires negotiation. Mobile testing is functional but feels secondary vs the web-prototype workflow.

What to pilot before signing. Run three real studies on the Free or Starter tier — one prototype test, one survey, one card sort. Have a non-researcher (PM or designer) author and analyze each. If the AI synthesis produces themes you''d defend in a stakeholder readout and the Figma integration removes friction, the value is obvious. If you find yourself manually re-coding every theme or fighting prototype imports, the workflow won''t scale and a more researcher-centric tool (Dovetail for synthesis, UserTesting for moderated) may fit better.', now());
